<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Campbell 1stLd-Writethru a0800 10-22 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Campbell, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Longest Tenured Federal Judge, Capone Prosecutor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Campbell, who ..., to deletel reference to
prison.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge William J.
Campbell, who prosecuted gangster Al Capone and was the
longest-tenured federal judge in the United States, has died of
complications from surgery. He was 83.
   Campbell, who died Wednesday, was one of the prosecutors who got
the notorious Chicago hoodlum convicted on tax-evasion charges.
Capone died in 1947.
   Campbell, appointed to the federal bench in 1940 by President
Franklin D. Roosevelt, rose to become chief judge in Illinois'
northern district and twice declined a seat on the 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
   He also was considered for a position to the Supreme Court.
   ``As a judge, he brought a dignity to the office that has seldom
been matched,'' said Chicago attorney Don H. Reuben. ``When you
were in his courtroom, you knew you were in a courtroom.''
   A New Deal liberal, he fought passionately against a Chicago
social club that refused to admit a black federal judge and for a
public defender program in the federal courts.
   During the stormy 1968 Democratic National Convention in
Chicago, Reuben said Campbell calmed a group of protesters in his
courtroom with demands for ``proper courtroom behavior.''
   Campbell retired in 1970 but continued to hear federal cases in
Illinois, California and for the past nine years at the federal
courthouse here.
   Funeral services were scheduled Friday.
   He is survived by his wife, Marie A. Campbell, five daughters
and three sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
