<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupportiveOpponent     10-22 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supportive Opponent,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenger In Connecticut State Senate Race Thinks Opponent Would
Do Better</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHELTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For most political candidates, it usually
goes without saying that they think they could do a better job than
their opponents.
   Not so in a state Senate race.
   Steven Debish, 20, of Shelton says he wouldn't mind voting for
Republican incumbent George Gunther on Nov. 8.
   Debish is the Democrat challenging Gunther.
   ``(Gunther) would probably do a better job, be more effective in
the next two years because of his long standing in the Senate,''
Debish said earlier this week. ``Most of the things I see in the
newspaper that he stands for, I agree with.''
   Debish, a sophomore at Southern Connecticut State University in
nearby New Haven, gives himself a very slim chance of defeating the
11-term incumbent.
   ``I just don't want to upset anybody,'' Debish said. ``He's
doing his job.''
   Many challengers demand face-to-face confrontations in debates,
but a few weeks ago Debish declined to meet Gunther in a debate.
   ``We decided he has so much experience, he would probably just
kill me,'' Debish said. ``He's just an old pro. I wish I had his
experience in public speaking and debating.''
   Debish's entry into the contest wasn't exactly a direct result
of a mandate or groundswell of support by local party leaders.
   ``Well, they needed a person to go up against him and I guess
they couldn't find anyone. Almost anyone who goes up against him
would probably lose,'' he said.
   Debish said he wanted to get some experience running for office
and has his sights set on something other than the Legislature. ``I
want to be mayor of Shelton someday,'' he said.
   Despite Debish's deference to the incumbent, Gunther can't quite
remember his challenger's name.
   ``What is it? Devlin? Dempsey?'' Gunther asked recently.
</TEXT>
