<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Trump-Shuttle     10-22 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trump-Shuttle,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Plans Major Upgrading of Eastern Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump says he's considering
such amenities as valet parking in upgrading Eastern Airlines'
shuttle service, and plans to spend ``tremendous amounts of money.''
   Trump agreed Oct. 12 to purchase the profitable Northeast
shuttle from parent Texas Air Corp. for $365 million in cash. If it
survives government scrutiny and a legal challenge by some of
Eastern's unions, the sale is expected to be completed by Dec. 15.
   The operation, which links New York with Boston and Washington
and is used mostly by business travelers, will be renamed the Trump
Shuttle. The blue-silver Eastern aircraft will be redecorated and
emblazoned with red, black and gold stripes, and will carry Trump's
name on their tails.
   ``I want to run an absolutely quality operation,'' Trump said
Friday in a telephone interview. The real estate magnate said he is
ready to spend ``tremendous amounts of money on each individual
airplane'' to accomplish his goal.
   The interiors of the 17 Boeing 727s will be completely redone
using high-quality leather, carpeting and other materials, Trump
said. He pledged to also stress safety by having each plane
thoroughly checked and X-rayed, using procedures Trump claimed
would be more stringent than Miami-based Eastern currently employs.
   The shuttle's airport terminals in New York, Boston and
Washington also will be refurbished, Trump said. He said he is
thinking seriously about introducing valet parking at the three
airports for shuttle customers _ a service that would likely be an
industry first.
   Trump said these improvements would take priority over possible
plans to expand the shuttle service to Atlantic City, N.J., where
he owns three casino-hotels. The developer runs a helicopter
service between New York and Atlantic City.
   Trump asserted that he will be able to carry out his expensive
plans without raising fares on the shuttle, which competes with a
rival service operated by Pan Am Corp.
   ``I'm just going to do it,'' he said. ``It's a substantial
investment, but it's something that has to be done.''
</TEXT>
