<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--ArtTheft     10-22 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Art Theft,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Recover Stolen Paintings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARNHEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A missing painting worth $175,000 was
found in the home of a 62-year-old woman who allegedly lifted the
masterpiece off its hook at a museum and tucked it in her shopping
bag, Dutch television reported.
   ``Landscape With Farmhouse And Haystack'' by the 17th-century
Dutch master Jan van Gooyen, was stolen from the Twenthe National
Museum in Enschede on Wednesday, according to the television report
Friday.
   The report said the woman had simply lifted the painting off its
hook and hidden it in a shopping bag during the museum's opening
hours.
   According to the report, the woman had also taken a self
portrait by modern Dutch artist Charley Toorop from the National
Museum Kroeller-Mueller near this eastern Dutch city in June. That
painting was worth $20,000, the report said.
   The report did not whether the woman has been charged.
</TEXT>
