<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   10-22 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Goes On The Attack As Bush Stays Home Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis went on the attack heading into a
weekend of campaigning from the deep South to New England, while
Republican George Bush was staying home today as the race for the
White House approached its final two weeks.
   The Democratic presidential nominee, lagging behind Bush in the
polls, was taking his case to television, both in a series of new,
fiery commercials and in news interviews as he sought to raise his
stock among the voters.
   In his television commercials, unveiled Friday, Dukakis calls
Bush's attacks on his record ``full of lies and he knows it.''
   However, the Bush campaign has responded that the ads are
truthful.
   Dukakis, who has been criticized for lacking passion, appears
angry in an ad titled ``Counterpunch.''
   ``I'm fed up with it,'' he says as he clicks off a television
set showing a ``negative'' commercial for Bush.
   The Bush commercial, showing Dukakis riding in a tank, attacks
the Massachusetts governor on defense issues. But Dukakis says in
his ad that both candidates want a strong defense.
   ``So this isn't about defense issues. It's about dragging the
truth into the gutter. And I'm not going to let them do it,''
Dukakis says.
   Bush, meanwhile, called for an international agreement allowing
on-site inspections on demand to enforce a ban on chemical weapons.
   ``The eventual combination of chemical weapons and ballistic
missiles could put new destructive power in the hands of
governments with terrorist records,'' Bush told an audience of
about 1,200 at the University of Toledo in Ohio.
   However, Bush did not mention that as vice president, he cast
tie-breaking votes in the Senate in 1983 and 1986 in favor of U.S.
chemical weapon arsenals.
   Those votes disturbed Bush's mother, Dorothy, who criticized him
after the second vote and then received a call from President
Reagan explaining why her son voted as he did.
   Bush today was meeting at his home in Washington with Armando
Valladares, who was freed six years ago after serving 22 years in a
Cuban prison. Valladares, who wrote about his ordeal in the book
``Against All Hope,'' has been cited by the vice president as one
of his heroes.
   Bush also planned to attend an Italian-American dinner tonight
in Washington.
   Dukakis, too, was to attend that dinner, but his appearance was
scheduled for later in the evening.
   The Democrat was starting his day with a joint appearance with
vice presidential running mate Lloyd Bentsen before a group of
pipefitters in Beaumont, Texas, before heading to a barbecue in
Georgia and then a television interview in Atlanta. Later he was
flying to Washington and then to Boston.
   Dukakis, who was taping an interview today with CNN, has made
himself available for network television interviews over the last
couple of days as he seeks to seize the offensive in the remaining
days of the presidential campaign.
   But Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle said the
Democrats' fall in the polls is so steep, there can be no return.
   ``We have a strategy to win Tennessee,'' Quayle said.
``Actually, I think the man from Massachusetts ... they might end
up on election night maybe having a one-state strategy or maybe
they'll just have a District of Columbia strategy.''
</TEXT>
