<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FetalTissue     10-22 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fetal Tissue,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Recommends Fetal Tissue Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Institutes of Health advisory
committee says it is ``acceptable'' to use the tissue from
intentionally aborted fetuses in medical research.
   However, the panel's 13-3 vote making that fundamental finding _
the core question it was asked to decide _ carefully avoided taking
a position on the morality of abortion itself or, for that matter,
the morality of using the remains of planned abortions for research.
   ``It is of moral relevance that human fetal tissue for research
has been obtained from induced abortions,'' said the draft document
completed Friday. ``However, in light of the fact that abortion is
legal and that the research in question is intended to achieve
significant medical goals, the panel concludes that the use of such
tissue is acceptable public policy.''
   It went on to say that the committee position ``must not obscure
the profound moral dimensions of the issue of abortion, nor the
principled positions that divide scholars, scientists and the
public at large. It is not the charge of this panel to attempt to
settle the issue of abortion or to weigh the worthiness of
competing principled perspectives on abortion itself.''
   Researchers are hopeful that transplanting fetal brain cells
into the brains of people with diabetes and Parkinson's disease
could provide an effective treatment _ perhaps in three to five
years _ and that more study could lead to similar treatments for a
number of other serious diseases for which there now is no cure.
   The new procedure has been used experimentally on a handful of
patients in other countries with promising results. The advisory
committee was formed to examine moral, ethical, legal and
scientific issues after NIH scientists sought permission to
transplant fetal brain cells into some Parkinson's sufferers.
   The committee's agreement on a lengthy draft document Friday
will not become final before Nov. 30, the date for submission of
mail ballots on whether to adopt the exact language that will be
written by NIH employees working to polish the principles adopted
by the panel over five days of discussion going back to last month.
   In the draft version approved Friday, the panel laid out a
number of recommended safeguards once research proceeds:
   _``The decision to terminate a pregnancy and the procedures of
abortion should be kept independent from the retrieval and use of
fetal tissue.''
   _``Proper and informed consent should be obtained from the
pregnant woman.''
   _``Payments and other forms of remuneration and compensation
associated with the procurement of fetal tissue should be
prohibited, except payment for reasonable expenses occasioned by
the actual retrieval, storage, preparation and transportation of
the tissues.''
   _``Potential recipients of such tissues, as well as any and all
other participants, including researchers, hospital personnel and
other service-providers, should be properly informed as to the
source of the tissues in question.''
   The panel also concluded that donations of fetal tissue to a
family member or acquaintance for medical purposes should be banned
to discourage women from becoming pregnant with the intention of
having an abortion and donating the tissue to a sick relative or
close friend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSTesting     10-22 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Testing,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends Changes In AIDS Testing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Kraemer is cq in final graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Screening tests for the AIDS virus are more
accurate than two years ago, but medical practitioners should have
at least two tests performed before informing an infected patient
that he has the disease, according to a study by experts.
   Thomas A. O'Brien, a Du Pont Co. expert on AIDS testing, said
some medical workers are still telling patients that they have the
disease after only a single test.
   ``The current tests are very, very good, but they are not 100
percent,'' O'Brien said Friday. He noted that only 10 percent of
patients testing positive in an initial screening test for AIDS
actually have the disease.
   O'Brien presented a report compiled by testing experts after
three days of discussion at the National Bureau of Standards. The
report recommends that AIDS testing should not be considered
definitive until both screening and confirmatory tests are
completed. And, in some cases, even further testing is needed.
   He said the testing sequence should start with a screening test
called ELISA (for enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay). For those
with a positive ELISA test, he added, there should then be a
confirmation test called a Western Blot.
   Both laboratory tests are based on the presence in the patient's
bloodstream of antibodies to the human immunodeficiency virus, or
HIV, which causes AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``If you test 10,000 people for HIV, the current tests would
give an ELISA positive on 0.2 percent (or 20),'' said O'Brien.
``Out of the 10,000, the Western Blot (confirming test) would be
needed only on those 20 samples.''
   O'Brien said that only about 10 percent of people testing
positive by the ELISA test are actually infected with AIDS. As a
result, he said, ``You don't tell someone that they are HIV
positive on ELISA alone.''
   Some samples, O'Brien said, cannot be confirmed as positive or
negative even with both ELISA and Western Blot. He said the expert
panel recommended that this ``indeterminate'' group undergo
additional and different tests before a final report is made to the
patient.
   AIDS is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune
system and makes it incapable of defending against infection. The
disease is not now curable, and no one has been known to recover
from it. As of Monday, there have been 75,768 AIDS cases reported
in the United States, and 42,653 have died.
   AIDS testing was one of four subjects addressed in a unique
gathering of medical testing experts at the National Bureau of
Standards. The group included testing specialists from government
agencies, industry and hospitals. Officials said the purpose of the
three-day meeting was to draw up recommendations for assuring that
the nation's laboratories are providing accurate testing.
   The group issued recommended ways to improve testing for AIDS,
for drug abuse, for cholesterol, and for the Pap smear cancer
screening test.
   Among the recommendations were:
   _Though testing for cholesterol was found generally to be
accurate in hospital laboratories, the group recommended that
cholesterol measurements made in a physician's office laboratory
should be studied, since these labs often are not part of a routine
quality control program.
   _A common system of measuring the presence and concentration of
drugs in urine tests should be established nationally. The experts
said that there now exists a common reference material (a sample
containing pure drugs at known concentrations) for marijuana, but
not for other controlled drugs such as cocaine, PCP or
amphetamines. The report said that such a common reference material
would increase the accuracy of drug testing.
   _The panel also said that the analysis of urine specimens can
identify an exposure to drugs, but it does not measure the level of
impairment. The experts recommended that research be conducted to
determine how such impairment can be measured accurately.
   _The experts said that false-negative findings in Pap smears, a
test for the presence of cervical cancer, are running as high as 4
percent to 8 percent, but that these errors often are a result of
poor technique in collecting specimens. The panel recommended that
the Pap specimen collection technique be standardized and that
women patients receive better instructions in how to prepare for
this test.
   Dr. Beverly B. Kraemer, a laboratory director at St. John's
Mercy Medical Center in St. Louis, Mo., said though there are
inaccuracies in Pap smear tests, the procedure is still ``a woman's
best friend'' in the war against cancer and ``one of the most
successful lifesaving laboratory procedures'' now commonly used.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
