<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TVA-Nuclear     10-22 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TVA-Nuclear,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA Charged With Violating NRC Regulations Through False Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Repeated false statements by the head of the
Tennessee Valley Authority's nuclear program constitute a violation
of federal regulations by the TVA, the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission charges.
   However, the commission said it has decided not to take action
on the original statements by Steven A. White, a former head of the
Navy's nuclear submarine program, ``as a matter of prosecutorial
discretion.''
   The NRC also decided, according to a letter sent Friday to TVA
Chairman Marvin Runyon, not to assess a fine because ``a civil
penalty for this matter is not necessary to further focus the
attention of either TVA or the industry on the importance of
complete candor'' in dealing with the commission, the letter said.
   The TVA Board of Directors, in a statement read by spokeswoman
Becky Akers, defended White while praising the NRC's decision not
to assess a fine.
   ``We continue to believe that Admiral White did not intend to
mislead the NRC on this or any other matter,'' the statement said.
   ``We are pleased that the Nuclear Regulatory Commission did not
fine TVA upon completion of this investigation,'' according to the
statement. ``However, we are disappointed that TVA received a
notice of a violation on statements relating to Appendix B. ... The
TVA board is fully committed to operating a safe and reliable
nuclear power program.''
   The NRC's letter said the TVA has 30 days to admit or deny the
allegations and to show what corrections it has undertaken if the
charge is admitted.
   The case concerns a March 1986 letter White wrote to the
commission. White had been hired a few months earlier to shape up
TVA's nearly collapsed nuclear effort that had seen the closure of
five reactors.
   White wrote the NRC that there had been ``no pervasive breakdown
of the quality assurance program'' at the Watts Bar plant under
construction near Spring City, Tenn.
   He repeated that assurance in a follow-up letter and in
statements to NRC investigators, adding that he had received a
review of the program by outside experts.
   In fact, according to previous commission testimony to Congress
and according to Friday's letter, White had not even spoken with
seven of the nine people he identified as constituting the outside
review group, and the two people he did speak with had not reviewed
TVA's quality assurance efforts but had only given opinions of the
work of an earlier in-house group.
   ``No one identified by Mr. White as being a member of the second
group understood there to be such a group,'' the letter said.
   In April, Ben B. Hayes, director of the NRC's Office of
Investigations testified before a congressional panel that White
was playing word games. Hayes told the investigations subcommittee
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee that White apparently
was intending ``pervasive'' to mean ``100 percent.'' While
technically true, TVA's quality assurance had serious and
widespread problems, he said.
   At the NRC staff, an internal group headed by James Taylor,
assistant executive director for operations, concluded that White's
statements were not deliberately false. The matter was referred to
the Justice Department, which has refused to comment on the status
of the case.
   White has denied any wrongdoing and has been supported by the
TVA board. He is retiring in January.
   The letter, signed by Taylor, now deputy executive director for
regional operations, said the violation was being assessed even
though White is leaving because ``TVA management as a whole is
responsible for the quality of communications with the NRC.''
   ``Both the individuals involved and the organization must share
responsibility for the actions giving rise to these violations, but
the fundamental premise of our regulatory system makes TVA, as the
licensee, ultimately responsible,'' the letter said.
   ``The NRC must be confident that it can rely on the information
furnished by a licensee,'' the letter said. `` ... Anything less
than accurate and complete statements to the commission cannot and
will not be tolerated.''
</TEXT>
