<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-22 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Sees ``One State Strategy'' For Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic slide in the polls is so
steep that Michael Dukakis could be left with a ``one state
strategy'' on election day, Republican vice presidential nominee
Dan Quayle said.
   And as he stumped through the South on Friday, Quayle worked to
steal a line his Democratic counterpart used to devastating effect
in the vice presidential debate.
   Dukakis, he declared, ``is no Harry Truman'' and won't be making
a comeback.
   A confident-sounding Quayle said there's a sharp contrast
between Republican and Democratic election strategies.
   Quayle told college students in Tennessee that the GOP has a
``50-state strategy'' and made light of reports that Dukakis is
narrowing his focus to about 18 states with enough electoral votes
for a win.
   ``We have a strategy to win Tennessee,'' Quayle said.
``Actually, I think the man from Massachusetts ... they might end
up on election night maybe having a one-state strategy or maybe
they'll just have a District of Columbia strategy.''
   The quip that Dukakis ``is no Harry Truman'' comes straight from
Democrat Lloyd Bentsen who scored the premier moment of the vice
presidential debate when he told Quayle, ``You're no Jack Kennedy.''
   Quayle described a conversation between Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr., and his father, a former senator.
   ``I guess he (Gore Jr.) called home and talked to his dad, when
his father told him that this reminded him of the Truman campaign
in 1948,'' Quayle said. ``Let me tell you something, I don't know
Michael Dukakis, I never served with Michael Dukakis, Michael
Dukakis is not a good friend of mine.
   ``But I know this: Michael Dukakis is no Harry Truman,'' said
Quayle.
   Bentsen used precisely that cadence in setting up Quayle for his
debate zinger, and aides said Friday's speech was the first time
Quayle had referred to the put-down in a campaign appearance.
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush had also set the
stage when he used a similar line in a self-deprecating fashion
during a dinner in New York on Thursday night.
   Quayle insisted the comparison was apt because many were
``trying to compare the Dukakis campaign to the Truman campaign.''
   Truman was perceived to be trailing throughout the 1948
campaign, but ended up defeating Republican Thomas Dewey.
   Most polls show the GOP ticket this year with a persistent lead,
and Quayle insisted there will be no comeback this time around.
   During his Southern swing, Quayle spoke to the college students
in Tennessee at a noisy rally where critics and backers competed
for attention, repeatedly interrupting the candidate.
   ``They've always been negative and they always will be,'' Quayle
said. ``They are the party of failure. We are the party of success.
   ``They can go ahead and yell,'' he said. ``We're going to talk
about issues and ideas.''
   Throughout his Southern swing, Quayle took a tough stance
against a tax increase and in favor of defense as he courted
conservative voters in a region where most polls suggest Bush is
strong.
   At a flag-waving riverside rally in Georgia, Quayle made a frank
appeal for backing from conservative southern Democrats.
   Dukakis, he argued, is ``not in the southern Democratic
tradition of national defense. Disenchanted Democrats are fed up
with liberalism.''
   He got some cheering news from the crowd, including one sign
which read ``Thank God Quayle is no JFK.''
</TEXT>
