<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Marcos-NoPromises     10-22 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos-No Promises,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials: Never Promised Marcos Anything</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Marcos Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indicted former Philippine President Ferdinand
E. Marcos received no promises from U.S. officials to persuade him
to leave his country without bloodshed during a popular,
military-based revolt in 1986, officials say.
   More than 2{ years after he fled the Philippines, Marcos, his
wife, Imelda, and six others were indicted Friday on racketeering
charges involving a vast fortune the Marcoses allegedly stole from
the Philippines.
   Action by the White House, a federal appeals court and the
Philippine government opened the final doors to that indictment
which came in a New York investigation that began shortly after
Marcos was airlifted to Hawaii in February 1986.
   Robert G. Rich, a former U.S. Embassy official in Manila who was
State Department liaison with Marcos during his first three months
of Hawaiian exile, said Friday that no high official, including
President Reagan, made any promises to Marcos.
   ``We offered refuge because the prospect of violence threatened
him and his family and to avoid a very bloody confrontation in the
Philippines,'' Rich said in a telephone interview from Belize,
where he is now the U.S. ambassador. ``There is no indication that
anyone at high levels offered anything inappropriate.''
   Marcos claims in a lawsuit filed in Honoluu that he was deceived
into leaving his country against his will.
   The case against Marcos has involved discussions with
Philippines officials and months of dealings among the White House,
Justice Department and State Department. Both State and Justice
department sources confirmed that there were disagreements over how
to handle the case, with Justice wanting to indict prior to plea
bargaining with Marcos and State urging a pre-indictment attempt to
bargain.
   A plea bargain which Marcos rejected was described by one
official as an attempt to get Marcos to return his vast wealth to
the Philippines, which is the main objective of the case. The
government of President Corazon Aquino alleges that Marcos and his
associates took out of the country $5 billion to $10 billion, much
of it stashed in Swiss banks.
   The way was cleared for the indictment after a White House
announcement Thursday that Reagan would ``not prevent the law from
taking its course.'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater later
said Reagan was saddened by the court action because Marcos was a
friend.
   Reagan had invited Marcos to the United States, and
administration officials were concerned about the impact the
indictment would have on U.S. credibility in dealing with foreign
rulers in the future.
   Fitzwater said after the indictment, ``We didn't make any
promises we couldn't keep. Any foreign leader can take our word on
anything.''
   Another administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Marcos apparently came to the United States because
it was where he ``felt safest and most comfortable. If he went to
another place, he might end up ripped off by another authoritarian
ruler.''
   But Rich said he believes that Marcos in 1986 probably planned
to stay in the United States only for a few months, miscalculating
the viability of the Aquino government and the lack of interest
other countries had in taking him.
   He and his wife are restricted to the island of Oahu because of
his attempt last year to return to the Philippines. U.S. officials
say they are honoring a Philippine government request that he not
be allowed to return.
   On Wednesday, the U.S. Court of Appeals in New York upheld a
civil contempt finding against Marcos and his wife for failing to
turn over evidence to the grand jury that handed up the
indictments. That decision also rejected Marcos' pleas for immunity.
   Last week, the Philippine government issued a formal waiver of
any immunity Marcos might be allowed from prosecution as a former
head of state.
</TEXT>
