<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     10-22 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Takes To Airwaves To Battle Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAUMONT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is on the air with four
new hard-hitting commercials and tonight is delivering a
five-minute televised appeal for support.
   The Massachusetts governor got a rousing reception Friday night
from several thousand people who filled the gymnasium on the campus
of the University of New Orleans.
   ``At the rate we're going, we're going to be importing 50
percent of our oil by 1990,'' he said.
   ``Even before we're inaugurated, Lloyd Bentsen and I are going
to call a bipartisan energy summit for this country ... and that
summit will be chaired by the vice president-elect of the United
States.''
   The commercials and television speech are the latest effort by
the Democratic presidential candidate to pick up momentum in his
race against Republican George Bush.
   ``The central point (of the new ads) is the Bush campaign and
their advertising are not to be believed,'' said campaign press
secretary Dayton Duncan.
   The new Dukakis ads started running Friday in key states.
   Television was the latest weapon in the Dukakis effort to
overtake Bush and emerge as an upset winner on Election Day, a
little more than two weeks away.
   His five-minute speech will air at 10:55 p.m. EDT, on ABC. Aides
said the Democratic candidate also would appear Tuesday night on
the ABC show ``Nightline.''
   Dukakis campaigned Friday in New York, Pennsylvania, and
Louisiana before flying to Texas for the night.
   At Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Harlem, Dukakis
renewed his pledge to wage a war on drugs and said, ``Our
determination to win this war should know no bounds.''
   His next stop was McKeesport, Pa., where he told a crowd that
waited in the rain, ``Don't let anyone tell you the steel industry
is dead in this country. It isn't, it's not going to be and we are
going to help bring it back.''
   Actor Albert Brooks, who starred in the movie ``Broadcast
News,'' was on the platform with Dukakis and told the crowd, ``I'm
a liberal and I'm a great guy.'' Then turning to Dukakis, he said,
``This guy's a liberal, he's a great guy.''
   Two of the new Dukakis television ads were responses to Bush
attacks on the Massachusetts prison furlough program and on
Dukakis' positions on defense issues.
   ``Bush won't talk about the thousands of drug kingpins
furloughed from federal prisons while he led the war on drugs,''
says one Dukakis ad. ``The real story about furloughs is that
George Bush has taken a furlough from the truth.''
   The Bush campaign is running a television ad that shows Dukakis
riding in a tank and describes him as opposed to a range of major
weapons systems.
   The Dukakis response shows the Democratic nominee watching the
opening moment of that ad and then turning it off.
   ``I'm fed up with it,'' says Dukakis. ``Haven't seen anything
like it in 25 years of public life, George Bush's negative TV ads.''
   The other two ads attack Bush for failing to stop the flow of
drugs into the country and for planning to cut the capital gains
tax, what Dukakis describes as ``tax breaks to the rich.''
</TEXT>
