<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0783 10-22 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0783,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Threaten Hostages In Retaliation For Israeli Air Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with photograph confirmed as
same as April photo, PICKS UP 8th pvs `The 29-line...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem kidnappers on Friday
threatened to harm two American hostages to retaliate for Israeli
air attacks on Palestinian and pro-Iranian guerrilla bases in
Lebanon.
   ``Committing this stupidity and this attack shall not pass
without a punishment,'' said a typewritten statement in Arabic
signed by Islamic Jihad, the pro-Iranian faction holding American
journalist Terry A. Anderson and educator Thomas Sutherland.
   The typewritten Arabic statement was delivered to the
independent Beirut newspaper An-Nahar hours after the attack. An
authenticating color picture of Anderson was delivered to the
Reuters news agency with a copy of the statement, but it was the
same photograph the group released of Anderson in April.
   The statement praised the Shiite Moslem suicide car bomber who
killed seven Israeli soldiers and wounded eight soldiers and two
Lebanese women in Israel's self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon on Wednesday. That attack prompted Israel's retaliatory air
strike, which killed 15 people and wounded 35 in south Lebanon on
Friday.
   The instant photo showed Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, wearing a Commodore Hotel
T-shirt and a bushy beard and mustache. He looked straight into the
camera without his glasses.
   It was the 11th picture released of Lebanon's longest-held
foreign captive, abducted in Moslem west Beirut March 16, 1985.
   It was the same photograph released of Anderson on April 10,
when Islamic Jihad threatened to harm the hostages if a Kuwaiti
jetliner hijacked to Larnaca, Cyprus was stormed to free the
passengers.
   The 29-line statement began with several verses from the Koran,
Islam's holy book, and deplored Israel's air attack as a
``challenge to the will of our oppressed people.''
   It accused the U.S. administration of giving Israel advance
approval to attack Palestinian and Hezbollah guerrillas in Lebanon.
The pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, had claimed
responsibility for the suicide bombing.
   ``The criminal America must realize it will not get away with
what it has done, especially in connection with the hostages we
hold, so that will be a lesson to whoever strikes at the dignity
and glory of our people and mujahedeen (holy fighters),'' it said.
   Sheik Fadlallah, considered to be Hezbollah's spiritual leader,
said he would do his best to protect the hostages.
   ``We continue to respect our previous commitments to defend
human rights in order to see these hostages free and safe as soon
as possible,'' he said. ``We will do our utmost to see that nothing
happens to any of them.''
   He spoke in Beirut with Ray Barnett, a Canadian representative
of Ambassadors of Aid, a group that helps orphans in Third World
countries.
   In Cadiz, Ky., Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, issued a statement
asking his captors to ``recognize that Terry Anderson is totally
innocent and has never been involved in the continuing Middle East
strife except as a captive for 3{ years.''
   ``It is totally unjust to hold him responsible for the military
actions of another country,'' Mrs. Say said.
   Friday's statement was the first since Aug. 18, when the group
said none of its hostages would be released soon.
   Sutherland, 56, of Fort Collins, Colo., was acting dean of
agriculture at the American University of Beirut when he was
abducted June 9, 1985.
   Anderson and Sutherland are among nine Americans believed held
by pro-Iranian extremist factions linked to Hezbollah. Others held
are three Britons, an Irishman and an Italian.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman called
for an end to violence between Israel and Lebanon and urged the
kidnappers to free their hostages.
   Asked about the Islamic Jihad warning, he said: ``These are
innocent victims. They are being held through no fault of their
own.... And the appeal to the hostage-holders has to be always,
`Release these innocent people.'''
   In a separate development Friday, the weekly Beirut magazine
Ash-Shiraa said the United States and Iran were working out a new
deal to free the American hostages before the U.S. presidential
election on Nov. 8.
   Ash-Shiraa said the deal would ensure the victory of Vice
President George Bush in exchange for a commitment from the
Republican candidate to rearm Iran.
   There was no way to verify the report. The United States has
stressed that it has no contacts with Iran.
   Ash-Shiraa, which has access to Iranian hardliners, gained
international fame in Nov. 1986 when it broke the story of the U.S.
secret arms sales to Iran. But most of its subsequent reports about
the hostages have been inaccurate.
   Other reports have said both Bush and Democratic candidate
Michael Dukakis sent envoys to work out a deal with the Iranians on
the hostages. Both candidates denied the reports.
</TEXT>
