<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0843 10-22 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0843,0390</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Jones; Separates moved for AMs as a0800 on Campbell and
as a0815 on Isbell. Isbell also moved on the business wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>William Campbell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Campbell, a U.S.
District judge who prosecuted gangster Al Capone and was the
longest-tenured federal judge in the United States, died Wednesday
of complications from surgery. He was 83.
   Campbell was one of the prosecutors who got the notorious
Chicago hoodlum convicted on tax-evasion charges. Capone died in
prison in 1947.
   Campbell, appointed to the federal bench in 1940 by President
Franklin D. Roosevelt, rose to become chief judge in Illinois'
northern district and twice declined a seat on the 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
   He retired in 1970 but continued to hear federal cases in
Illinois, California and for the past nine years at the federal
courthouse in West Palm Beach Florida.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Marion Isbell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marion William Isbell, the Ramada Inc.
founder, died Thursday at the age of 83.
   In 1954, Isbell and a group of Phoenix investors began buying
motels. In 1960 he decided to assemble the motels into a chain
owned by a publicly held company, and two years later became
chairman of a 63-motel chain known as Ramada Inns Inc.
   Under his leadership, Ramada Inns expanded to 500 motels in 45
states, and later into Canada, Mexico, Brazil and overseas. Isbell
ran the Ramada chain as president and chief executive officer until
1973 and retired as chairman in 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Jones</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Jones, a Omaha television personaliy,
who played Dr. San Guinary on KMTV's ``Creature Feature'' program,
died Thursday of cancer. He was 46.
   Jones worked at KMTV from 1965 until the time of his death. He
began at the station as a floor manager and went on to become a
producer-director and in recent years, an account executive.
   Jones was most widely known for his Saturday night appearances
on ``Creature Feature,'' a program that ran from 1971 until 1982
and featured horror movies.
   As Guinary, Jones donned green makeup, a red wig and a white
smock smeared with what looked like blood. The character provided a
light touch as he introduced the horror movies.
</TEXT>
