<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarketShootings     10-22 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Shootings,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer Gets Life In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to life in prison without
parole Friday for his role in the murders of five people during a
supermarket robbery last year.
   Marvin Jennings, 27, of Overland, was sentenced to the maximum
penalty on each of 16 counts, including five terms of life without
parole.
   St. Louis Circuit Judge Thomas C. Mummert III, following a
jury's recommendation that Jennings be given life imprisonment
rather than the death penalty, ordered that the sentences be served
consecutively.
   At the sentencing, Jennings continued to assert his innocence.
   During the Sept. 4, 1987, robbery at a store here, seven workers
were ordered to lie on the floor and were shot execution-style. Two
survived.
   Jennings was convicted Sept. 10 of armed robbery and multiple
counts of murder, assault and armed criminal action.
   The other suspect in the crime, Donnie Blankenship, 26, of
Hanley Hills, is to be tried early next year on identical charges.
</TEXT>
