<HEAD>House Action Blocked on Sanctions Against Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House action on sanctions to punish Iraq for
its alleged use of poison gas against the Kurdish minority was
blocked early Saturday, and the Senate Foreign Relations chairman
blamed manuevering by House members beholden to ``special
interests.''
   Committee Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., told the Senate it
was ``almost a tragedy'' to allow a handful of House members to
bottle up the sanctions bill in the last hours of the 100th
Congress.
   ``The will of the majority, the will of the Congress has been
repudiated,'' he said.
   The Senate had initially passed a strong set of sanctions
against Iraq in the wake of reports that the Iraqi army had
subjected Kurdish villages to gas attacks. It later went along with
a watered-down compromise version originating in the House.
   But that compromise died when it was stripped from a pending tax
bill.
   ``Unfortunately, special interests got into the act,'' Pell told
the Senate.
   He said opposition to sanctions against Iraq had developed in
the American agriculture, oil and chemical industries.
   ``The net effect has been to kill the Iraq sanctions for this
Congress,'' said Pell, who vowed to revisit the issue early in the
101st Congress next year.
   He said that for now he is concerned that Iraq will get ``the
wrong message'' and that the Kurds may be placed in further peril.
</TEXT>
