<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-22 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUNTA GORDA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man's wedding night turned into the
jailhouse blues when a deputy who performed the marriage returned
to arrest him.
   Anita Clough, bride-to-be of Ronald Jackson, recruited Sheriff's
Deputy Robert Cook, who's also a notary public, to conduct
Thursday's ceremony.
   ``I thought it would be a really nice idea,'' Cook said. ``This
would be a nice change of pace, I told myself, and I'd be helping
these two kids out.''
   At Jackson's home, Cook said he thought Jackson looked familiar.
Jackson, 18, explained that the deputy had ticketed him in the
past. Cook put that out of his mind and performed his first wedding.
   But Jackson's explanation stuck in the back of his mind, Cook
said.
   ``I ran a computer check on Jackson, and I couldn't believe it
when it came back,'' the deputy said. ``He had three outstanding
warrants pending, for what else _ failing to show up in court on
the tickets I wrote him.''
   Cook turned his patrol car around and arrested Jackson.
   ``I almost wished I had any other job in the world but the one I
had,'' the officer said.
   After spending his wedding night in jail, Jackson was released
on bond Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doug Winton, an adjunct professor at
Rochester Institute of Technology's College of Continuing
Education, teaches basic physics to adult, part-time students who
couldn't care less about the subject.
   ``They're mostly business majors. This is their required science
credit. So I try to add a little pizazz,'' he said.
   The pizzaz works. Total strangers have turned up in class just
to gawk at the magic tricks Winton employs to make physics exciting.
   His first trick is a variation of the old
whisk-the-tablecloth-off-a-set-table trick. He stacks up four
glasses of water, a cookie sheet, four cardboard tubes and four
jumbo eggs.
   ``The secret is jumbo eggs. They're heavier, so they have more
inertia,'' Winton says.
   When the cookie sheet is knocked away, the eggs drop into the
glasses because, as Winton's students know, bodies at rest want to
stay at rest and bodies in motion want to stay in motion.
   He demonstrates the importance of velocity by driving a large
nail into a piece of plywood with his hand wrapped in a towel. His
grand finale is lying on a bed of nails and having a trained
volunteer smash cinder blocks with a sledgehammer, first on his
abdomen, then on his forehead.
   The laws of physics offer protection, but no guarantees. Raw
knuckles, a bruised hand, a scraped scalp and a mild concussion
sometimes are part of the act.
   ``I've had students who couldn't bear to look,'' Winton said.
</TEXT>
