<HEAD>Dozens Killed In Clashes With Rebel Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes this month between the army and
guerrillas left 56 soldiers and 30 rebels dead, state-run Radio
Rangoon reported.
   The broadcast Friday said the highest death toll _ 21 soldiers
and 18 rebels _ was in the Shan States, one of many areas of the
country plagued by an insurgency by ethnic groups demanding greater
regional autonomy.
   The 83 clashes with ``various rebel groups'' Oct. 1-21 left 110
government troops wounded and six others missing, the radio said.
   A government spokesman earlier said that from Sept. 26 to
Monday, 35 government soldiers were killed and 95 wounded in those
battles, which are continuing. He said rebel casualities were
believed to be heavy.
   Friday's announcement mentioned only two troops and three rebels
killed in Karen State.
   The guerrilla groups have been fighting the government for the
past four decades.
   The government also has acknowledged that besides the
insurgents, its troops killed more than 450 people since Gen. Saw
Maung seized power in a coup Sept. 18. Western diplomats say the
victims included large numbers of people peacefully demanding
democracy, but the government says most were looters and other
``destructive elements.''
   While banning pro-democracy demonstrations, Saw Maung's
administration has allowed formation of opposition parties and
promised a general election sometime next year.
   The radio said four more parties registered Friday, bringing the
number of officially recognized parties to 32.
   The four new parties included two parties of the Chin minority
group _ the Zomi National Congress and the Chin National League for
Democracy. Four other minority-based parties registered earlier.
   The broadcast added that announcements will be made later on the
registration of a dozen more parties.
</TEXT>
