<HEAD>Caterpillar And UAW Work On Final Contract Snags</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf, ``Union officials ...,'' to
UPDATE with tentative agreement in Aurora, Peoria; picks up 7th
graf, ``Union sources ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc. and the United Auto
Workers announced a tentative agreement Friday on a new labor
contract for 17,500 workers in five states.
   Bargainers had been working against an 11 p.m. Friday strike
deadline on an agreement for union workers at Caterpillar plants in
the Illinois cities of Decatur, Peoria and Aurora, the only union
locals that had not previously reached a tenatative settlement.
   Details of the agreements were not immediately released.
   Earlier Friday, UAW Local 2096 of Pontiac, Ill., with 648
members, announced it had reached a tentative agreement.
   Pontiac was the fourth UAW local to reach a tentative agreement
with the Peoria, Ill.-based Caterpillar, the world's largest maker
of earthmoving equipment. Contract talks started Aug. 4.
   Union officials had said those locals without a tentative
agreement by the 11 p.m. deadline would be authorized to call a
strike.
   Minutes before the strike deadline, the Aurora local reached a
tentative agreement, said UAW negotiator Elliott Anderson. The
Peoria local followed suit about an hour later.
   Union sources earlier said a special job classifications was the
main snag in talks with the Illinois UAW locals in Decatur, Peoria
and Aurora.
   Those three locals represent 14,400 of Catepillar's 17,500 UAW
workers.
   After months of bargaining and two contract extensions, both
sides announced Thursday that a tentative agreement had been
reached on nearly every key issues, including pay raises and
improved health and pension benefits.
   The locals had objected to the creation of a special job
classifications for highly technical jobs because they said it
threatened the union's traditional seniority system.
   Workers trained to fill these high-tech positions could not be
bumped from their jobs by untrained workers with more seniority who
faced layoff.
   Company officials maintained, however, that management could not
afford to invest in new automated machinery and specialized job
training unless it could depend on having those workers remain on
the job.
   UAW locals in Denver; York, Pa.; and Memphis, Tenn., earlier
reached tentative agreements and the Davenport, Iowa, plant is
being closed.
</TEXT>
