<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sakharov     10-22 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Physicist Credits Recent Reform For Travel Permit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Andrei D. Sakharov says the
government's approval of his first foreign trip, with visits to as
many as six U.S. cities next month, is a result of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's recent reforms.
   The 67-year-old physicist who spent eight years in exile in his
own country for human rights campaigning, told a Friday news
conference that authorities agreed ``in principle'' to the trip but
have not yet issued travel documents.
   ``I consider that the positive response making my trip possible
stems from the very big changes in our country during the last few
years,'' said Sakharov, who won the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his
human rights activities.
   The lifting of the travel ban against Sakharov, father of the
Soviet dissident movement, marked another reversal in Kremlin
policy by Gorbachev, who has liberalized Soviet society on many
fronts.
   Sakharov said he plans to attend a meeting in Washington of a
philanthropic group called the International Foundation for the
Survival and Development of Humanity.
   Sakharov is to attend the foundation's board meeting in
Washington Nov. 15-16 and meetings in Los Angeles, San Francisco,
Boston, New York and possibly Chicago, said group member Edward B.
Hodgman.
   The foundation was set up in January to help solve
environmental, human rights, disarmament and economic development
problems.
   The U.S. State Department welcomed the Soviet decision but urged
Moscow to give the same permission to all Soviets wishing to travel
abroad.
   ``Soviet use of alleged knowledge of state secrets to deny many
other Soviet citizens the right to travel abroad is deplorable and
inconsistent with Soviet commitments under the Helsinki Accords,''
said spokesman Charles Redman.
   Sakharov's trip could set an uncomfortable precedent. Hundreds
of citizens have been denied permission to travel abroad on grounds
they know state secrets.
   He had been denied permission to travel on grounds he had access
to sensitive information while working on the Soviet hydrogen bomb
in the 1950s.
   Sakharov has spoken out repeatedly for free emigration and
protested the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan in 1979.
   He was exiled to the closed city of Gorky in 1980 and released
under Gorbachev's administration in December 1986.
   In another sign of his return to good graces of Soviet
officials, Sakharov was elected one of 47 members to the ruling
Presidium of the prestigious academy. During the now-disgraced rule
of President Leonid Brezhnev, some academy members tried to expell
Sakharov.
   Sakharov said the academy voted 152-82 to elect him to the
Presidium, its leading body. Tass said Sakharov now is conducting
research in cosmology, the study of the universe's origin.
   The physicist said his wife, Yelena Bonner, would not travel
with him but will travel later to the United States alone for
medical treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
