<1ST_LINE>u w PM-TaxBill     10-22 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Bill,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Approves Tax Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress today completed action on a bill
cutting taxes by $4.1 billion and increasing the clout of
individuals involved in disputes with the Internal Revenue Service.
   With only a half-dozen members on the floor, the Senate approved
the bill by voice vote and sent it to President Reagan, who,
backers predict, will sign it. The House had endorsed the
compromise a few hours earlier on a 395-1 vote.
   ``There are thousands and thousands and thousands of people who
are going to be beneficiaries and they'll thank us for doing our
job,'' said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas.
   Those thousands include farmers, who will be relieved of paying
the federal tax on diesel fuel used for off-road purposes and will
no longer have to fret with the paperwork caused by the ``heifer
tax'' on livestock. Other winners include owners of mutual funds,
free-lance writers, workers who receive tuition payments from their
employers and families saving for a child's college education.
   But taxes on other groups will have to go up by $4.1 billion
over three years to pay for the $4.1 billion of selected tax cuts.
   The losers include pipe smokers, who, for the first time, will
have to pay a tax of 45 cents on a pound of their favorite smoking
mix; anyone accustomed to writing off part of their basic home
phone charge; investors in single-premium life insurance policies,
and some corporations, especially those owned by native Alaskans.
   Alaska corporations would lose a special benefit that has
allowed them to sell operating losses to profitable companies.
Lawmakers say the provision has been abused.
   Negotiators who drafted the final legislation accepted most of
the ``taxpayer's bill of rights,'' written chiefly by Sen. David
Pryor, D-Ark., which is aimed at tipping the scales slightly more
toward taxpayers when they face audit or collection actions by the
IRS.
   These provisions were approved in response to a growing concern
among many lawmakers about isolated reports of taxpayers being
harassed and intimidated by some IRS employees.
   In the future, the IRS would have to fully inform taxpayers of
their rights and recourses before any audit or collection steps are
taken. The agency would have to give a 30-day notice, compared with
10 days in current law, before seizing property to pay back taxes,
and it would be barred from promoting employees on the basis of how
much money they collect.
   The legislation, more than two years in the making, was designed
originally to clear up typographical errors and ambiguous wording
in the big tax overhaul enacted in 1986. It grew in size as the
tax-writing committees tacked on amendments extending some expiring
provisions and granting tax benefits for selected groups.
   A major non-tax provision seizes 540 acres of land adjacent to
the Manassas Battlefield in northern Virginia to block construction
of a shopping mall on the site. The Reagan administration opposes
this provision, although there has been no indication whether it
would prompt a veto.
   Negotiators, meeting behind closed doors, dropped another
unrelated provision, which would have imposed economic sanctions
against Iraq to protest that nation's use of poison gas against
some of its Kurdish citizens.
   Major provisions would:
   _Exempt from tax interest earned on U.S. savings bonds that are
redeemed to pay for college, starting Jan. 1, 1990.
   _Extend expiring tax benefits to help lower-income families buy
their first home; reward businesses for increased spending for
research and experimentation, and boost incentives for investment
in low-income rental housing.
   _Renew an expired provision that allows workers to exclude from
income tuition payments made by their employers; most graduate
study would not qualify.
   _Extend an exclusion for the value of employer-financed
legal-service benefits.
   _Prohibit a business deduction for the basic monthly cost of a
home telephone.
   _Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to deduct
certain expenses before a project starts producing income.
   _Permit owners of mutual funds to deduct certain operating
expenses of the fund without having to meet a requirement that only
miscellaneous expenses exceeding 2 percent of income be deducted.
   The single House vote against the bill was cast by Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
