<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     10-22 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gregory Peck will receive the
1989 American Film Institute's Life Achievement Award, the
organization's chairman announced.
   Peck, who received an Academy Award for ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' in 1962, will be honored March 9 at the institute's
annual award dinner at the Beverly Hilton Hotel. The event will be
broadcast on NBC.
   ``Gregory Peck joins a distinguished group of individuals who
have made enormous contributions to America's film heritage,''
AFI's new chairman, Gene Jankowski, said in announcing the award
Friday.
   Peck began his acting career in 1939 and took off in various
Broadway productions, including ``Morning Star'' and ``Sons of
Soldiers.''
   His theatrical successes brought him to Hollywood. He received
Academy Award nominations as best actor for ``The Keys of the
Kingdom,'' ``The Yearling,'' ``Gentleman's Agreement'' and ``Twelve
O'Clock High.''
   His portrayal of southern lawyer Atticus Finch in ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' won him his fifth nomination and the Oscar.
   Previous Life Achievement winners include Jack Lemmon, Barbara
Stanwyck, Billy Wilder, Gene Kelly, Lillian Gish, John Huston and
Frank Capra.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Peter Fonda, answering critics of his
support of the ``bottle bill'' initiative on the Nov. 8 ballot,
says being a Montana resident for 14 years gives him the right to
speak out on state issues.
   Earlier this week, Montana recyclers who oppose the measure
calling for a mandatory deposit on bottles criticized Fonda's
appearance in a television commercial.
   Fonda, the brother of actress Jane Fonda and star of the 1969
film ``Easy Rider,'' responded with a news conference here Friday,
introducing himself as ``Peter Fonda, a Livingston actor. Not a
Hollywood actor; I live in Livingston.''
   Fonda reiterated his contention that the proposal would expand,
not diminish, recycling in Montana. He supplied copies of letters
from governors, mayors and others endorsing mandatory deposit laws.
   ``I want to also make it clear that I do not appreciate the
attitude or methods used by Montana's recyclers,'' said Fonda, who
has a ranch in the Paradise Valley near Livingston. ``Living here,
I should have a right to speak out in Montana without being called
names.''
   Fonda said he had neither given nor received money in connection
with the referendum campaign, but had donated his services because
he believes in the need for a deposit law.
   ``I'm not even getting lunch out of this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: `Cambell' in last graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The English rock group Duran Duran publicized
its latest album, ``Big Thing,'' by giving a free concert for 5,000
fans in a Hollywood parking lot.
   The concert outside the landmark Capitol Records building was
part of a tour designed to ``give people a chance to hear the music
in small settings,'' said Capitol spokeswoman Dorene Lauer.
   The nine-city, small-venue tour began Wednesday in San Francisco.
   At Thursday's open-air concert in Hollywood, the band performed
songs from their new album as well as older hits such as ``Hungry
Like the Wolf,'' ``Girls on Film,'' ``Reflex'' and ``Rio.''
   The band includes original members Simon LeBon, Nick Rhodes and
John Taylor, and new members Warren Cuccurullo and Sterling Cambell.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKE TAHOE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright David
Mamet, who's expressed distrust for Hollywood in previous works and
statements, seems to have mellowed somewhat in his attitude toward
Tinseltown.
   ``I'm learning all kinds of lessons from Hollywood all the
time,'' Mamet said in a recent interview here.
   At the moment, Hollywood is treating the feisty playwright
rather well.
   The 40-year-old writer, who won the Pulitzer for his play
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' is getting the royal treatment for
``Things Change,'' a Columbia Pictures release that opened Friday.
   Mamet co-wrote and directed the comedy about a gangster, played
by Joe Mantegna, who lures a shoeshine man, played by Don Ameche,
to the gaming tables here.
   Mamet has written 10 plays and four screenplays. In addition to
his Pulitzer, he has garnered an Oscar nomination. His play,
``Speed-the-Plow,'' which opened on Broadway in May and starred
Mantegna, Ron Silver and Madonna, shows his view of Hollywood as a
cutthroat town with a dollar-sign mentality.
   Mamet divides his time between a Vermont farm and a home in
Cambridge, Mass.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALPHAMSTONE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of actor Michael Caine's
partners in a restaurant suffered serious burns when fire broke out
at his home after what police called a ``serious domestic
incident'' with his wife.
   Peter Langan, 47, was listed in serious but stable condition
Friday night in a burn unit at St. Andrew's Hospital in Billericay.
His wife, Susan, 46, was treated at Colchester General Hospital and
released after breaking her ankle in a jump from a window.
   A police source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
fire had not begun when Mrs. Langan leaped from a first-floor
balcony from the 10-room house in Alphamstone, Essex, about 50
miles northwest of London.
   ``We do not know whether the fire was started deliberately,'' he
said. He said a ``serious domestic incident'' had occurred before
the fire broke out.
   Chef Richard Shepherd, one of Langan's restaurant partners, said
it was ``a pure accident'' which started when an oil heater in
their bedroom caught fire.
    Langan's Brasserie, one of London's best-known show business
gathering places, is co-owned by Langan, Shepherd and Caine.
</TEXT>
