<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     10-22 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Anemia Lessens, But Kidneys, Liver Worsen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larger-than-usual blood transfusions in recent days
have improved Emperor Hirohito's anemia, but court officials said
today that his kidney and liver functions are worsening.
   Doctors have stopped using antibiotics to treat the 87-year-old
monarch's infected bile duct, said Kenji Maeda, the Imperial
Household Agency spokesman.
   Maeda said only that physicians ``believed it was necessary to
do so,'' but news reports quoted palace sources as saying the
infection had declined and doctors were concerned about side
effects from prolonged use of strong drugs.
   Hirohito received another transfusion of 0.4 of a pint Friday
night, Maeda said. That brought the total he has been given since
his condition worsened on Sept. 19 to 24 pints _ nearly three times
as much as is normally in his body.
   Kyodo News Service quoted unnamed palace sources as saying the
emperor's liver functions were worsening and that the nitrogen
level in his blood was three times above normal.
   Palace officials said the emperor had not discharged any blood
for two days, but doctors believed his internal bleeding was
continuing.
</TEXT>
