<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hershiser,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hershiser Sings Hymn on Johnny Carson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orel Hershiser, appearing on ``The Tonight
Show starring Johnny Carson,'' sang a few bars from the hymn he
said lifted his spirits when the pressure was on during the World
Series.
   On the urging of Carson and Friday's studio audience, Hershiser
warbled ``Praise God, from whom all blessings flow .... Praise
Father, Son and Holy Ghost.''
   The Christian hymn, known as the Doxology, dates back to 1695
and is based on text from Psalm 150.
   Carson, who appeared to be somewhat embarrassed and moved, said,
``That's very sweet.'' The audience responded with sustained
applause.
   Hershiser said he sung the hymn on the mound on Thursday as he
pitched the Los Angeles Dodgers to victory over the Oakland
Athletics in the fifth and deciding game of the World Series, which
the Dodgers won four games to one.
   Carson asked Hershiser, winner of the most valuable player
awards in this year's World Series and National League Championship
Series, what his future plans are.
   ``Retirement,'' the 30-year-old pitcher quipped.
</TEXT>
