<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-US     10-22 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-US,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Firebomb USO Facility After U.S. Soldiers And Koreans
Brawl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty students hurled firebombs at a
USO building after a brawl between Koreans and U.S. soldiers,
police and news reports said today.
   No injuries were reported in the attack Friday night on the
United Services Organization, a recreational body for American
soldiers based overseas.
   There also were no damages, U.S. military authorities said, even
though one firebomb cleared a fence but missed the building. Guards
immediately put out the blaze without incident, the authorities
said.
   Seoul newspapers said the attack involved 20 slogan-chanting
students who hurled about 10 firebombs at the American facility and
scattered leaflets demanding the U.S. government apologize for
assaults by American soldiers on Koreans.
   One American soldier and three Koreans were injured last Sunday
in a fight involving about 40 U.S. soldiers and 200 Koreans in
Itaewon, a shopping district close to the U.S. military
headquarters in southern Seoul.
   Radicals recently stepped up an anti-U.S. campaign in the
aftermath of the Olympics Games, when the actions and manners of
some American athletes and the allegedly biased coverage of Korea
by the U.S. media during the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 games upset many
Koreans.
   Dissidents demand the withdrawal of about 42,000 U.S. troops
stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact, contending
the United States hampers unification of the Korean peninsula.
   The peninsula was divided into the communist North and the
capitalist South in 1945, at the end of World War II.
   In another development, the U.S. Embassy has asked American
officials and athletes taking part in the International Paralympics
Games in Seoul to refrain from going to Itaewon at night, U.S.
officials said.
   Signs were posted in living quarters of American athletes, but
the embassy gave no explanation, they said.
   Bob Pearson, a spokesman for the U.S. team, said the embassy has
asked his team not to wear clothes or uniforms identifying
nationality during the visit to Itaewon.
</TEXT>
