<2ND_LINE>PM-APME-Public Service,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Inquirer, Alabama Journal Honored by AP Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philadelphia Inquirer and The Alabama Journal
of Montgomery were awarded the Associated Press Managing Editors
association's 1988 Public Service Awards.
   The Inquirer, in the 50,000-and-over circulation category, was
cited Friday for sifting the fine print of the 1986 Tax Reform Act
to report who had been specifically but anonymously granted tax
benefits.
   The Alabama Journal, in the under-50,000 circulation class, was
recognized for a three-month investigation resulting in stories
about the poverty that gives Alabama the highest infant mortality
rate in the nation.
   The plaques were presented at the APME convention here by the
chairman of the judging panel, Robert E. Rhodes, who is Gannett
Foundation professional-in-residence at the University of Kansas
and former executive editor of the Corpus Christi (Texas)
Caller-Times.
   The other finalists in the 50,000-and-over circulation category
were: Atlanta Journal and Constitution; Chicago Tribune; Cleveland
Plain Dealer; Lawrence (Mass.) Eagle-Tribune; Louisville (Ky.)
Courier-Journal; New York Times; Arizona Republic of Phoenix;
Rochester (N.Y.) Democrat and Chronicle, and St. Petersburg (Fla.)
Times.
   Under-50,000 circulation finalists were; Auburn (N.Y.) Citizen;
Boulder (Colo.) Camera; Bradenton (Fla.) Herald; El Paso (Texas)
Herald-Post; Pasadena (Calif.) Star-News; Portsmouth (N.H.) Herald;
Pottstown (Pa.) Mercury; Stamford (Conn.) Advocate, and Walla Walla
(Wash.) Union-Bulletin.
   The other judges, all former presidents of APME, were Larry
Allison, senior vice president and editor, Long Beach (Calif.)
Press-Telegram; James Daubel, editor and publisher, Fremont (Ohio)
News-Messenger; Michael J. Davies, editor and publisher, Hartford
(Conn.) Courant; Robert Haiman, chairman, The Poynter Institute;
Barclay Jameson, executive editor and general manager, Pueblo
(Colo.) Chieftain, and John Leard, retired executive editor,
Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch and News-Leader.
</TEXT>
