<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Carlucci-Arabs     10-22 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-Arabs,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says More Weapons Would Bring Peace To Mideast </HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HN1 of Oct. 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci says
Americans must get over their fear of selling arms to Arab
countries, or risk losing ground to other countries with the
weapons and the will to step in.
   ``Great Britain, France, China, the Soviet Union and others are
moving into the highly desirable positions of confidence and
influence which America has traditionally enjoyed with friends such
as Jordan and Saudi Arabia,'' Carlucci said. ``I see tens of
billions of dollars worth of jobs going abroad instead of
sustaining our key defense industries and bolstering the U.S.
economy.''
   Carlucci, speaking Friday at an American-Arab relations seminar
at Marshall University, said the threat to Israel would be greater
if Arab countries look to other nations to supply arms.
   ``The notion that U.S. defense cooperation with moderate Arab
states poses a danger to Israel is ill-founded and untrue,''
Carlucci said. ``Israel must regard non-American arms in the hands
of its neighbors as a higher risk.''
   Congress has rejected major arms sales to Saudi Arabia, and
Carlucci warned lawmakers that the denial poses a greater threat
militarily in the Mideast and economically in the United States.
   Fouad Al-Farsy, Saudi Arabia's deputy minister of information,
said earlier in the seminar that his country, like other moderate
neighbors of Israel, should not be treated as the enemy due to its
longstanding relationship with the United States.
   ``In the last 15 years, in the development of Saudi Arabia, we
have looked to the U.S. of America for leadership, guidance ... and
manpower,'' Al-Farsy said.
   The international president of B'nai B'rith, a Jewish civic and
fraternal organization, said the group was dismayed to hear that
Carlucci ``defined United States arms sales policy in terms of
dollars and cents.
   ``If the United States wanted primarily to earn monetary profit
on weapons sales, this country could sell arms to all sorts of
dictatorial and totalitarian regimes around the world,'' said
Seymour Reich.
   ``However, the cornerstone of the U.S. arms sales policy has
always been to examine first and foremost the strategic and moral
implications of military sales,'' Reich said.
   ``In the case of arms sales to the Middle East, the U.S. has
always chosen the wise course of supporting its most reliable ally
in the region, Israel,'' Reich said. ``This has meant, and rightly
so, denying sophisticated weapons to those nations who _ in
defiance of U.S. foreign policy which seeks advancement of the
peace process _ continue to declare themselves to be in a state of
war with America's steadfast partner in strategic cooperation,
Israel.''
   Carlucci and Al-Farsy agreed on the need for Israel and the
Palestine Liberation Organization to meet face-to-face to negotiate
peace in the Mideast, but had differing conditions for how to get
them talking.
   Carlucci said the PLO first needs to renounce terrorism and
agree that Israel has a right to exist.
   ``Palestinian participation is required at every stage of
negotiations concerning the West Bank and Gaza, since the outcome
will affect their interests and will bear directly on their future
as a people,'' Carlucci said. ``Without their active participation,
no agreement can be expected to endure.'' Al-Farsy said the United
States should not set itself up as an ``honest broker'' then take
Israel's side on every question.
   ``There can be no chance for peace if one side will not talk to
the other. To them, progress is the lack of progress,'' Al-Farsy
said of the Israelis. ``Israel is stubborn because it knows the
U.S. of America will support her no matter what position she
takes.''
</TEXT>
