<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Shooting,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas State Fair Shoot-Out Leaves One Dead, Three Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT G. WIELAND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shootout on the midway of the State Fair left
one dead and three wounded, including a police sergeant who was
shot in the hand as he grappled with gunman, authorities said today.
   Two other officers were hurt in scuffles, and numerous
bystanders were knocked down or trampled late Friday and early
today as thousands fled the scene of the gunfight just outside the
Cotton Bowl.
   Police were trying to determine what triggered the violence. The
shooting followed a brawl between black and Hispanic fair-goers,
said police Cpl. D.H. Boy.
   Police Sgt. Manuel Vasquez was in stable condition at Baylor
University Medical Center, where he underwent surgery, said Debbie
Mecham, a nurse at the hospital.
   The man who police said shot Vasquez died of multiple gunshot
wounds, Ms. Mecham said. His name was not released.
   The incident apparently began around 11:45 p.m. with a shooting
in a fair restroom, said police Capt. John Holt.
   An officer who overheard the shot chased two or three people
through the midway crowd and found the sergeant, the gunman, and
another man struggling on the ground, said Holt.
   A gunbattle ensued between the pursuing officer and the gunman,
the captain said.
   Two other men were shot in addition to the gunman and the
sergeant, he said. One was shot in the restroom and the other on
the midway.
   Both were in serious condition, one with a chest wound, the
other with a back wound, said a Parkland Memorial Hospital nurse
who declined to give her name.
   Thousands of people headed for exits when the shooting broke out.
   Seven pregnant women were treated for injuries or premature
labor caused by the fair-goers' stampede. Five other people were
trampled or bruised in the crush.
   Gloria Pena, 17, said she and a friend tried to climb a six-foot
chain link fence to escape the gunfire, but she could not make it
because she is seven months pregnant. She and her friend soon were
engulfed by the crowd.
   ``We were both crying and holding each other and didn't know
what to do,'' Ms. Pena said while waiting for hospital care. ``Then
she fainted.''
   Juan Salazar, 37, of Dallas, was high above the midway on the
Texas Star ferris wheel when the shooting began.
   ``I heard two or three shots and people in the center _ in the
middle _ started running in every direction,'' Salazar said.
``After that, you could see people in different spots just running
like crazy _ just getting away from this area.''
</TEXT>
