<DOCNO> AP881022-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseIndictment     10-22 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Indictment,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Colonel, Computer Contractor Indicted; Others Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-year probe that led to the
indictments of a retired Air Force colonel and a defense contractor
is likely to produce more charges, a federal prosecutor said.
   Unisys Corp. and its predecessor, Sperry Corp., are each accused
of falsely billing the government for more than $500,000 for work
that was never performed as part of a $526 million contract to
modernize the Air Force's computer network, U.S. Attorney Jim
Wilson said Friday.
   Retired Air Force Col. Robert L. Hedges, 51, of Montgomery is
accused of negotiating a consulting job with Sperry while he was
overseeing the contract, Wilson said.
   Wilson said more indictments are expected from the
investigation. Hedges was indicted Wednesday and the companies on
Tuesday.
   Hedges' Washington-based attorney, Robert S. Bennett, said his
client was innocent and would defend himself vigorously.
   ``His decisions regarding his post-retirement activities were
done in full accordance with the law and with the knowledge and
understanding of the Air Force,'' Bennett said.
   J. Peter Hynes, a spokesman at Unisys' office in Blue Bell, Pa.,
said ``neither (Hedges) nor Sperry did anything wrong.''
   Unisys is the product of the 1986 merger of Sperry and Burroughs
Corp. Wilson said that is why both companies were named in the
indictment.
   A statement released by Unisys said the company ``was
disappointed that, after more than three years of cooperation with
the government, an indictment would be brought relating to the
alleged falseness of one invoice of a predecessor company.''
   Al Agricola, an assistant U.S. attorney handling the case, said
investigators had not determined whether Sperry might have received
favorable treatment in exchange for a consulting job Hedges took
after he left the service in August 1984.
   ``Under the statute, it didn't have to. Just the conflict being
there is required,'' said Agricola.
   In June 1984, Hedges signed a $75,000 consulting contract with
Sperry while on leave from the Air Force, Wilson said.
   Hynes confirmed that Hedges did work for Sperry after leaving
the Air Force. He said Hedges is still under contract with Unisys.
   Sperry was awarded the eight-year contract in January 1983.
Wilson said Hedges oversaw the program from Gunter Air Force Base
in Montgomery.
   Prosecutors said Unisys remains eligible for defense contracts,
although Col. Clarence Benham of the Air Force's investigations
division said the Pentagon could decide otherwise.
   If convicted, Sperry and Unisys each could face $50,000 fines
plus restitution to the Air Force. Hedges could be fined $10,000 if
convicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
