<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Jordan-Mideast     10-22 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan-Mideast,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak, Arafat Arrive In Jordan For Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak accompanied
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat to Jordan today on Arafat's first visit
to the kingdom since King Hussein severed links last July with the
Israeli-occupied West Bank.
   Hussein greeted the leaders at the Red Sea port of Aqaba, 175
miles south of the capital Amman, state Jordan Radio reported.
   Palestine Liberation Organization officials in Tunis, reached by
telephone from Cyprus, said Arafat and Hussein are trying to agree
on a formula for a confederation between Jordan and a future
independent Palestinian state.
   The Palestine National Council, a sort of parliament-in-exile,
is due to meet in Algeria on Nov. 12-14 to declare Palestinian
independence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which have been
wracked by a Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule since Dec. 8.
   ``Mubarak believes that it (the council) will be successful only
if it also states clearly what relations the Palestinian state will
have with Egypt, Israel and Jordan,'' one PLO official said.
   The radio said among those gathered for today's talks were Prime
Minister Zaid Rifai and Foreign Minister Taher Masri of Jordan,
Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and three of Arafat's
senior aides, Hani al-Hassan, Mahmoud Abbas and Mohammed Milhem.
   Mubarak said in an interview published Thursday in the Egyptian
daily Al-Ahram that ``the next few days'' would witness ``a
consolidation'' of the Arab side in possible peace talks with
Israel.
   ``It is now for Israel to make up its mind and declare that it
opts for peace and is ready to accept the obligations peace
entails,'' he said.
   The tripartite summit comes a little more than a week before a
crucial Israeli election pitting the Labor Party, which favors
negotiating a partial withdrawal from the occupied territories,
against the Likud bloc, which opposes territorial compromise.
   Hussein said Thursday in an interview with the U.S. network
ABC-TV that a Likud victory would be ``an absolute disaster'' and
said the peace proposals of Labor leader Shimon Peres were a ``step
forward.''
   Arafat has not visited Jordan since the outbreak of pro-PLO
rioting in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which once again propelled
the PLO to the center of the Middle East stage.
   In July, Hussein formally renounced his claims to the West Bank,
which Jordan ruled until Israeli occupation in 1967. The move
challenged the PLO to set up a Palestinian state in the occupied
lands.
   Hussein said he took the move in compliance with PLO wishes. PLO
officials generally welcomed the move but expressed irritation they
were not consulted in advance and some indicated suspicion Hussein
was trying to pressure the organization.
   ``It's no secret that there's distrust between the king and the
chairman (Arafat),'' said a PLO official from Tunis. ``But both
trust Mubarak. He can be a good guarantor.''
   PLO officials say the Palestinian National Council is likely to
declare independence for the occupied territories that include
Gaza, which was ruled by Egypt before its occupation in 1967. It
may also establish a provisional government that could take part in
peace talks.
   PLO officials say the council may formally, but implicitly,
endorse Israel's right to exist by accepting the 1947 United
Nations partition resolution that split Palestine into Arab and
Jewish states.
   At least 301 Palestinians and six Israelis have died in the
10-month uprising in the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
