<DOCNO> AP881022-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Swindall     10-22 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swindall Faces Tough Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall cannot tell a jury that
charges against him were politically motivated without a hearing
that could delay his perjury trial until after the Nov. 8 election,
a judge ruled.
   Swindall accused U.S. Attorney Robert Barr of scheming against
him for political gain on Friday. He also charged that the
government deliberately timed his 10-count indictment shortly
before the election.
   ``They wanted to make darn good and well (sure) that they got
the indictment before Nov. 8, 1988,'' Swindall said of prosecutors.
   But U.S. District Judge Robert Vining, who began screening
potential jurors Friday, ruled that Swindall may not raise his
allegations to the jury without a hearing that could delay his
trial until after the election.
   Barring such a delay, jury selection could be completed and
opening arguments in the trial could begin Monday.
   Swindall told Vining he would pursue the hearing process ``if it
doesn't unnecessarily delay the trial,'' but lead prosecutor Craig
Gillen immediately served notice he would seek time to prepare a
written response to any such move.
   Barr also said he plans to be on the West Coast next week for
legal conferences.
   Vining said Swindall would be free to raise the issue Monday
morning. Outside the courtroom, Swindall declined to comment on his
plans.
   Swindall, a two-term Republican representing the 4th
Congressional District of suburban Atlanta, faces Democrat Ben
Jones in the election.
   As he unsuccessfully sought to subpoena Barr to testify at the
trial, Swindall contended it is no accident that he was indicted
shortly before the election.
   He accused Barr _ who, like Swindall, is a Republican _ of
contacting officials in Vice President George Bush's presidential
campaign to assess the political impact of his investigation.
   One of those officials, Jay Morgan, deputy director of Bush's
Southern campaign, confirmed he talked with Barr on the day
Swindall was indicted but denied ever having discussed the Swindall
case with Barr.
   Barr declined comment, citing the pending trial.
   Later, Swindall said he would subpoena reporters for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and WSB-TV, two news organizations which this
summer obtained transcripts or videotapes of secretly recorded
meetings between Swindall and an undercover investigator.
   Swindall would not disclose what he wants to ask the reporters
on the witness stand, and questioned whether they can legally be
compelled to reveal the source of their stories about the recorded
conversations.
   Meanwhile, Charles LeChasney, described by prosecutors as the
middleman in the loan negotiations which led to the charges against
Swindall, pleaded guilty to five violations of federal currency
laws.
   LeChasney admitted to charges which do not mention Swindall, but
involve the money-laundering ``sting'' investigation that
eventually included a proposed $850,000 home mortgage loan for the
congressman.
   Paul Kish, LeChasney's lawyer, said he did not know if his
client would be called as a prosecution witness against Swindall.
   LeChasney was a participant in meetings with Swindall and an
undercover agent posing as a financier. The government contends
that the agent told Swindall his proposed loan from LeChasney would
be backed by illegal drug proceeds and that Swindall perjured
himself by denying that to a grand jury.
   Swindall has said LeChasney misled him and that he did not
intentionally deceive the grand jury.
   LeChasney could be sentenced to 30 years in prison and fined
$1.5 million, but under a plea agreement, federal prosecutors
agreed to recommend lesser sentences if he testifies truthfully in
all related cases. Five related charges will be dropped under the
plea bargain.
   LeChasney also agreed to repay $17,500 in government funds which
he had converted to his own use.
</TEXT>
