<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--SlainOfficers     10-22 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Slain Officers,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral For Officers Killed by Barricaded Gunman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police officers attended separate
funerals for two Detroit officers who were killed as they tried to
arrest a barricaded gunman.
   Officer Frank Walls, 39, was eulogized Friday in a service at
Verheyden Funeral Home in Grosse Pointe Park. His remains were to
be cremated.
   About 100 police cars joined a funeral procession later Friday
for Lt. James Schmit, 41, who was buried at St. Charles Cemetery in
Newport.
   The officers were shot about five hours apart Monday as police
tried to flush out Charles Knowles, a 50-year-old described as
having a history of mental problems.
   ``We've lost two brothers. These deaths bring a special kind of
pain,'' Detroit Police Chief William Hart said before the funerals.
``It's a pain you never get used to, and it's a pain that never,
ever goes away.''
   The standoff with Knowles ended when he was fatally shot by
other officers. Schmit and Walls were the first Detroit officers
slain this year.
</TEXT>
