<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0460 10-22 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Welcomes Marcos Indictment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, ``Mrs. Aquino...'' to MOVE
UP Aquino quote. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Marcos has...'' Inserts 1
graf after 12th graf pvs, ``Mrs. Aquino's...'' to ADD quote from
Philippine official.
^By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today
welcomed the indictment of Ferdinand Marcos on U.S. racketeering
charges, saying it would hasten recovery of the billions of dollars
plundered during his 20-year rule.
   Mrs. Aquino, in a statement, said she hopes the prosecution in
New York of her predecessor will serve as a deterrent to other
dictators who steal from their countries and then seek asylum
abroad.
   ``This (indictment) is certainly welcome news in the Philippines
and I commend this evident commitment to the rule of law abroad,''
Mrs. Aquino said.
   Marcos has been living in Honolulu since he fled the country
during the February 1986 civilian-military revolt that swept Mrs.
Aquino to power. President Reagan invited Marcos to take up
residence in the United States.
   Marcos claims in a lawsuit filed in Honolulu that he was
deceived into leaving the country against his will.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, are restricted to the island of
Oahu because of his reported attempt last year to return to the
Philippines. U.S. officials are honoring a Philippine government
request that he not be allowed to return.
   On Friday, the U.S. government indicted former President Marcos,
his wife and eight associates on charges of racketeering. They
could face 20-year prison sentences if found guilty.
   Marcos was the highest-ranking former foreign official indicted
in the United States.
   The charges alleged that between September 1972, when Marcos
declared martial law in the Philippines, and 1986, the Marcoses
amassed $103 million through embezzlement, theft, bribes and
kickbacks.
   According to the indictment, the Marcoses illegally funneled the
money through secret bank accounts in Switzerland, Hong Kong and
the United States and then used the money to buy valuable New York
properties.
   ``I hope that this and other similar efforts undertaken in other
countries to investigate the crimes of the Marcoses will lead to
the early recovery of the stolen assets that rightfully belong to
the Filipino people,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   Mrs. Aquino's government has accused the Marcoses of stealing up
to $10 billion in public and private assets during Marcos' rule.
Mrs. Aquino formed the five-member Presidential Commission on Good
Government to try to recover the wealth and bring the Marcoses to
trial.
   The commission's former chairman, Ramon Diaz, said the U.S.
trial will save the Philippines time in efforts to recover assets.
``A lot of evidence that we would have to present before the U.S.
courts (to recover U.S. property) will already have been
presented,'' he said.
   In Bern, Swiss authorities have ordered records on some Swiss
financial transactions made by Marcos, saying those records can be
turned over to the United States.
   The Aquino government alleges that Marcos and his associates
stashed much of their funds in Swiss banks. Swiss authorities put
that figure at at least $1 billion.
   But Beat von Rechenberg, Marcos' Swiss lawyer, said he would
``most probably'' file an appeal with the Federal Tribunal,
Switzerland's Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
