<DOCNO> AP881022-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-ShipsCollide 2ndLd-Writethru   10-22 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ships Collide, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0504,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Seamen Dead, One Girl Missing in Cruise Ship Collision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Papandreou flying back to
Athens and promising probe. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``At the...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl was missing today after an Italian
freighter rammed a Greek cruise ship carrying 475 British students
and teachers, causing the cruise ship to sink, officials said. Two
seamen were killed.
   At least 64 people, including 30 students, were injured Friday
evening when the Adige freighter tore a gaping hole in the
6,300-ton Jupiter, which was steaming out of Piraeus harbor. Two
remained hospitalized today.
   Screaming children jumped from the listing ship into oil-covered
waters before the vessel sank less than an hour after the collision.
   A British Embassy official said the 14-year-old girl, Vivienne
Barley, was the only person still unaccounted for.
   A Merchant Marine Ministry official said radio appeals were
broadcast ``for anyone who may have seen her or picked her up to
contact us.''
   Frogmen and Coast Guard officials searched the area where the
Epirotiki Lines cruise ship sank less than a mile from Piraeus
harbor on the start of an eight-day educational cruise.
   ``The Italian ship tore a huge hole below the waterline, almost
splitting the Jupiter in two ... no wonder it sank in less than an
hour,'' said Spyros Mavrikis, an Epirotiki spokesman.
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, looking fit and well
after major heart surgery in London, flew to Athens today promising
a full investigation into the collision.
   At the time of the accident, the 415 teen-agers and their 60
teachers and helpers were on a trip to Greek islands and ports in
Egypt, Israel and Turkey.
   ``I was sitting with my friends in the lounge when we looked out
of the window and saw this ship coming straight towards us,'' said
14-year-old Kirsty Spurling, a pupil at the Sacred Heart of Mary
convent school at Havering in Essex county, England.
   ``We all screamed, there was a bang and the boat began to tilt
... I said a prayer,'' she said.
   As the cruise ship listed, screaming youngster jumped overboard
into the oily waters of Athens' main port. Others were thrown into
the sea by the force of the swell as the vessel sank.
   Dozens of Coast Guard launches and tug-boats rushed to the
rescue, but there were conflicting views as to how the survivors
managed to escape the vessel.
   ``The ship tilted at a terrible angle and very quickly. We were
all told to get out of the boat and climb up as high as we could,''
said Grahame Addecott, an English teacher at the Sacred Heart of
Mary school.
   ``On deck we were told to hang onto the rails and it seemed
forever until the crew helped us down into the rescue boat ... some
of my girls were very frightened,'' he said.
   Some students said crew members chose to abandon ship rather
than help the students into boats.
   ``The crew all got out leaving us there to look after
ourselves,'' said Stephanie Stavrou, 16, from Dunster Close
Romford. ``I didn't see any of the crew after we got out on deck.''
   Weeping, oil-splattered children and teachers clung to each
other as they boarded buses bound for hospitals in the Piraeus
area. Four passengers were reported to have fractures and one
underwent surgery for abdominal injuries, British Embassy officials
said.
   The rest of the group was taken aboard another Epirotiki Lines
cruise ship berthed in Piraeus _ the Pegasus _ for the night.
   The tour company Schools Abroad, which coordinated the trip for
13 schools across England, said charter jets were flying the group
home today. The first of four planes with 140 people aboard, some
still wrapped in blankets, took off from Athens Airport just before
1 p.m.
   Merchant Marine Ministry officials identified the two dead
seamen as Vassilis Psomas, 22, and Athanasios Golemotis, both from
the Jupiter's 120-member crew. Golemotis' age was not available.
   Merchant Marine Minister Evangelos Yannopoulos said the Italian
ship was to blame and its skipper, Capt. Flavio Caminale, was
arrested on manslaughter charges.
   The Adige, a container ship owned by Sicula Oceanica Spa, Siosa
Line, of Palermo, Sicily, was transporting automobiles to Piraeus
and hit the Jupiter while maneuvering toward the dock.
</TEXT>
