<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0520 10-22 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq To Release 25 Iranian POWs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to ADD more from spokesman's remarks. ADDS
byline. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``According to...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH PANOSSIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq announced today it will release 25
Iranian prisoners of war in accordance with a U.N. cease-fire
resolution, the official Iraqi News Agency said.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted an unidentified
spokesman of the Iraqi Foreign Ministry as saying the unilateral
decision was relayed to the International Committee of the Red
Cross.
   The spokesman was quoted as saying the Red Cross was asked to
disptach a delegation to Iraq ``to take the neccessary measures to
repatriate the POWs.''
   On Thursday, Iran rejected an Iraqi plan for repatriating
prisoners of war from the eight-year Persian Gulf conflict and said
Iraq must accept the U.N. plan for ending the war before prisoner
exchanges could start.
   The Iraqi spokesman was quoted as saying with the latest batch,
the total number of sick and aging Iranian prisoners released by
Iraq ``for purely humanitarian reasons, with no political
conditions attached'' reached 645.
   He called on Iran to reciprocate, adding Iran ``would be held
fully responsible for any delay in ending the sufferings of the
POWs and their families,'' the news agency reported.
   He said Iran ``has all along dealt with the POWs issue as a
political one, in order to exploit it for the puposes of Iran's
expansionist policies.''
   According to the Red Cross, Iran has 50,182 prisoners and Iraq
has 19,284 prisoners. But U.N. officials and diplomats in Iran and
Iraq believe Iran holds 60,000 to 70,000 POWs and Iraq 30,000 to
50,000.
   U.N. Resolution 598 calls for an immediate cease-fire,
withdrawal of troops to internationally recognized boundaries and
the exchange of prisoners.
   Iraq this week proposed to the International Red Cross and U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar that repatriation of
prisoners should begin on humanitarian grounds if Iran reciprocates.
   But Iraq also made it clear its offer was unrelated to peace
negotiations, which stalled five days after a cease-fire was
declared on Aug. 20.
   The peace talks have deadlocked over Iraq's insistence that the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms its southern border
with Iran, should be cleared of silt and ships sunk early in the
war.
   Iran has rejected the dredging demand, saying it is a secondary
issue that can be settled later in the negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
