<DOCNO> AP881022-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0513 10-22 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0513,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Jets Buzz East Lebanon, Kidnappers Threaten Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with interview with Nabih Berri.
Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``They've seldom...'' TRIMS thereafter to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes flew over the ancient
city of Baalbek in east Lebanon, police said today, fueling fears
of an imminent attack on the main stronghold of pro-Iranian
extremists.
   The rare nighttime overflights came hours after Israeli
fighter-bombers attacked other Palestinian and pro-Iranian
guerrilla bases to avenge the killing Wednesday of seven Israeli
soldiers in a suicide car bombing.
   Shiite Moslem kidnappers holding at least two American hostages
charged Friday that the United States gave advance approval to
Israel to strike at the guerrilla strongholds, and the kidnappers
threatened to harm the hostages.
   Nabih Berri, a Shiite Moslem leader, said today that the
kidnappers of the hostages committed an ``unforgivable crime'' by
threatening to harm them.
   Berri, who heads the mainstream Shiite Amal militia, spoke in an
interview with The Associated Press. Berri's Syrian-backed militia
has been locked in a fierce struggle with pro-Iranian
fundamentalists for mastery of the Shiite community, and,
therefore, has no influence on the kidnappers.
   Police in Lebanon said today that the death toll from the
Israeli air raids climbed to 16 when a wounded person died.
Thirty-four were hurt in the attack.
   Police said sonic booms jolted the population of Baalbek out of
their beds late Friday night and early this morning when the
Israeli jets crashed the sound barrier in several low-altitude runs
over Baalbek.
   ``They've seldom done such a thing since the 1982 invasion,''
said a police spokesman. ``People are afraid their city will be the
next target for Israel's retaliation to the suicide bombing.''
   Baalbek is controlled by the Iranian-backed fundamentalist group
that is believed to be the umbrella for kidnappers of the 14
foreigners in Lebanon.
   An estimated 3,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards are based at the
Sheik Abdullah barracks on a hilltop overlooking the city that
harbors ancient Roman ruins.
   Hezbollah said victims of Israel's retaliatory raid were to be
buried today in a mass funeral in the Bekaa valley town of Mashgara.
   The air raids hit positions near Mashgara and the port city of
Sidon. Israeli officials often charge that Hezbollah and the PLO
cooperate in guerrilla warfare against Israeli troops and allied
militiamen in south Lebanon.
   Israel pulled most of its army from south Lebanon in June 1985
after a three-year occupation and carved out the six-to-10-mile
security zone to prevent guerrilla infiltration into its northern
settlements.
   Israel had vowed to retaliate for Wednesday's bombing, the
deadliest attack against Israelis in south Lebanon in 2{ years.
   ``Committing this stupidity and this attack shall not pass
without a punishment,'' said a typewritten statement in Arabic
signed Friday by Islamic Jihad, the pro-Iranian faction holding
American journalist Terry Anderson and educator Thomas Sutherland.
   The statement, delivered to the independent Beirut newspaper
An-Nahar hours after the attack, praised the Shiite Moslem suicide
car bomber.
   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was abducted in Moslem west Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Sutherland, 56, of Fort Collins, Colo., was acting dean of
agriculture at the American University of Beirut when he was
abducted on June 9, 1985.
   Anderson and Sutherland are among nine Americans believed held
by pro-Iranian extremist factions linked to Hezbollah.
   The statement accused the U.S. administration of giving Israel
advance approval to attack Palestinian and Hezbollah guerrillas in
Lebanon. The pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the suicide bombing.
   Sheik Fadlallah, considered to be Hezbollah's spiritual leader,
said he would do his best to protect the hostages.
   ``We continue to respect our previous commitments to defend
human rights in order to see these hostages free and safe as soon
as possible,'' he said.
   In Cadiz, Ky., Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, asked his captors
to ``recognize that Terry Anderson is totally innocent and has
never been involved in the continuing Middle East strife except as
a captive for 3{ years.''
   Friday's statement was the first since Aug. 18, when the group
said none of its hostages would be released soon.
</TEXT>
