<HEAD>FBI Agent Charged With Selling Cocaine To Undercover Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI agent has been fired after being arrested
for selling a small amount of cocaine, a bureau spokesman says.
   Roderick Kimmons, 36, of Chicago, is accused of selling a
quarter-gram of cocaine to an undercover agent for $40 at a
nightclub Thursday, and a gram of the drug to a cooperating witness
for $100, FBI spokesman Bob Scigalski said.
   ``We heard rumors last week that he had been selling cocaine,''
said agent James McKenzie. ``When we hear something like that, we
make it a priority'' to make an arrest.
   Kimmons, an eight-year veteran, was arrested Friday and charged
with felony possession and distribution of a controlled substance,
and immediately dismissed, Scigalski said.
   Kimmons posted a $4,500 recognizance bond after arraignment. He
faces a maximum 20-year prison term if convicted.
