<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NativityScene     10-22 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nativity Scene,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Court Says OK to Nativity Scene On City Hall Lawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday display that features a nativity
scene and Hanukkah menorah may be displayed on the city hall lawn
because it creates ``no real danger of establishing a state
church,'' a federal judge has ruled.
   The American Civil Liberties Union, which opposes the display,
says it will appeal Thursday's ruling but will await the U.S.
Supreme Court's decision on a similar case involving the city of
Pittsburgh.
   The ACLU contends the display contains religious symbols and
violates the First Amendment's separation of church and state.
   U.S. District Court Judge James Harvey ruled that Warren's
Christmas display does not endorse a particular religion and
``poses no real danger of establishing a state church as prohibited
by the First Amendment.''
   In December, U.S. District Judge Lawrence Zatkoff denied a
motion by the ACLU to remove the display, saying he found the
display secular in nature. Besides the creche and the menorah, the
display contains large candles and soldiers and incorporates the
city's Vietnam memorial.
</TEXT>
