<HEAD>Policeman Urges Chinese Leader to Quit Smoking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese newspapers published a reader's letter
urging leader Deng Xiaoping to launch an anti-smoking campaign by
kicking the habit himself, a Hong Kong newspaper reported Saturday.
   Policeman Zhang Jianxin wrote that by smoking in public, Deng
encouraged thousands of Chinese to keep smoking, the independent
Chinese-language Ming Pao reported, quoting the Hong Kong China
News Service.
   The news agency was quoted as saying China's Health Newspaper
gave the letter prominent play and that it also ran in the Hygiene
Newspaper. Chinese media traditionally do not criticize China's
leaders.
   Zhang, of the northwest Xinjiang province, said he hoped Deng
will quit for his and the Chinese peoples' health.
   The agency said China produced 40 billion packs of cigarettes
annually and 250 million people smoke. It said of the 32,000 fires
last year, more than half were caused by careless smokers.
