<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     10-22 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Kill Party Leader, 12 Untouchables</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists shot and killed 13
people Saturday, including a state leader of the governing Congress
Party, police said.
   Nachattar Singh, a Congress leader and president of the Punjab
National Motor Transport Union, was gunned down as he got off a bus
in the village of Badhni Khurd, police said.
   In Firozpur district, five men with AK-47 Chinese-made assault
rifles opened fire on a group of people in a resettlement colony
near the Pakistan border. Twelve were killed and seven were
wounded, police said.
   The United News of India news agency said the victims, members
of India's lowest caste, were brewing illegal liquor along a canal.
   Sikh extremists fighting for an independent nation were blamed
for both attacks, the agencies said.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are a
slight majority in Punjab, a prosperous farming state bordering
Pakistan. They claim they are oppressed by the majority Hindus.
