<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia-Future Bjt   10-22 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Future, Bjt ,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalism And One-Party Rule Hinder Reform in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In dealing a blow to an ambitious
Serbian politician, Yugoslavia's Communist leaders have shown how
difficult it is to quell ethnic turmoil or introduce democracy in
this one-party state.
   With millions watching on television, the Communist elite last
week ended 38 hours of bitter debate with a dramatic rebuff to
Serbian Communist party leader Slobodan Milosevic.
   A close ally of Milosevic, Dusan Ckrebic, was the only member of
the ruling Politburo not to win a secret vote of confidence
Wednesday from the party's policy-setting Central Committee.
   Ckrebic, an old-time Communist in his 60s, immediately offered
his resignation. But Milosevic angrily intervened to stop
consideration of the offer, and Ckrebic remains on the Politburo
for now.
   Another Ckrebic ally charged that an ``unprincipled coalition''
tried to bring Ckrebic down to hurt Milosevic.
   The meeting, which did little to tackle the growing economic
crisis, gave Yugoslavs a revealing look at their squabbling
leadership.
   Serbs who have rallied round Milosevic's campaign for greater
Serbian control over the provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina were
furious that only a Serb _ Ckrebic _ fell victim to the
unprecedented vote of confidence for Politburo members.
   ``Did you see what they did to us?'' fumed a Belgrade television
journalist.
   The next day, 20,000 Serbs in Kosovo protested the outcome.
   Chanting ``We will not give up Ckrebic!'' they literally turned
their backs on two Politburo members who came to address complaints
that the Central Committee session did nothing to meet their
demands.
   The 200,000 Kosovo Serbs and Montenegrins, a minority in what
was once a Serbian heartland, want to end alleged harassment by the
ethnic Albanian majority. They also want to oust some ethnic
Albanian Communist leaders.
   The call for action extends far beyond Kosovo. With inflation at
217 percent and living standards halved since 1980, most of
Yugoslavia's 23 million people are fed up with leaders they
perceive as ineffectual and corrupt.
   The Central Committee's response to the widespread demand for
new leaders was the vote of confidence and the prospect that a
third of the committee's 165 members would be replaced in the next
six weeks.
   That would constitute the single biggest sweep of top party
ranks since Stalinists were purged after Yugoslavia's break with
Moscow in 1948.
   But it fell short of widespread expectations of an immediate
shake-up, and the choice of who should fall is likely to get mired
in the usual battle among the party leaderships of Yugoslavia's six
republics and two provinces.
   The broad powers given those eight leaderships under the 1974
constitution have enabled widely varying political cultures to
develop.
   The most obvious gap is between the rich, Western-oriented north
and the bankrupt, backward southern areas of Montenegro, Macedonia
and Kosovo.
   Another rift has opened up between liberal northern Slovenia and
the demagogic populism of Serbia's Milosevic.
   Party chief Stipe Suvar, from the republic of Croatia between
Slovenia and Serbia, hailed the vote of confidence in Politburo
members as a step to party democracy.
   But the way Milosevic tried to undo the verdict showed clearly
that however much he supports economic and even political reform,
he will protect Serbia's and his own interests first.
   The leaders agree that change is needed, Suvar said after the
Central Committee meeting. But he said the party's only experience
in cleaning its own house is in purges ordered from the top.
   ``We are still learning the rules of the game,'' he said.
   The half-hearted steps toward political reform show how hard it
is for any one-party system to change without the Communists either
relinquishing power to some form of popular control or simply
carrying out a ruthless purge.
   Stane Dolanc, a former No. 2 to the late Josip Broz Tito, said
during the Central Committee's debate that the crisis probably cost
Yugoslavia ``a billion dollars'' in lost foreign investments.
   Suvar tried to assuage what he said were foreign fears that
Yugoslavia is descending into chaos.
   ``Yugoslavia will not fall apart,'' he said. ``There is a great
deal of quarreling in Yugoslavia, but it is not as dangerous as it
may appear at first glance.''
   But Western creditors are likely to remain uneasy about
recovering any of Yugoslavia's $21 billion foreign debt.
   Economic and constitutional reforms designed to attract foreign
and private investment are lumbering their way through party and
government organs this fall.
   For years, Yugoslavs have called for such reforms _ and more
radical ones, such as a return to private farming in this largely
agricultural nation.
   Ironically, the political struggle fueled by the ambitions of
Milosevic may deter foreign investors just as Yugoslavia opens up
to capitalist investment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alison Smale, The Associated Press bureau chief
in Vienna, regularly covers Yugoslavia and traveled to Belgrade for
this story.
</TEXT>
