<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Opposition     10-22 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Opposition,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Invite Opposition Leader Kim Dae-jung</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's top opposition leader,
Kim Dae-jung, has received an invitation from a Soviet institute to
visit Moscow, aides said Saturday.
   Kim got the invitation last week from Georgy Arbatov, a member
of the Soviet Communist Party's Central Committee, the aides said.
   The letter from Arbatov, who also heads the U.S.-Canada
Institute, a Kremlin think tank, said Kim would be able to get a
Soviet visa at any Soviet Embassy overseas, with no dates
specified, they said.
   South Korea has no diplomatic relations with communist nations
and the Soviets have no diplomatic mission in South Korea.
   Kim was considering his visit to Moscow ``affirmatively'' but
has made no decision, the aides said.
   They said Arbatov also wanted to read Kim's studies about
political and other issues involving the United States, the Korean
peninsula and the Pacific region.
   Kim heads South Korea's largest opposition group, the Party for
Peace and Democracy, and aides have said he still wants to run for
the presidency again at the end of President Roh Tae-woo's
five-year term.
   Roh took office in February after winning last December's
presidential election over divided opposition candidates.
</TEXT>
