<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-22 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barbecued buffalo sandwich once
bitten into by Richard M. Nixon is being preserved for posterity by
an Illinois family.
   Steve Jenne, now 42, was a Boy Scout in his native Sullivan when
Nixon, then vice president, sank his teeth into the sandwich. Jenne
walked off with the uneaten portion and his family has kept it in a
deep freeze since.
   ``It'll probably stay frozen forever,'' Jenne said recently.
``It's been a part of the family for 28 years.''
   Nixon, then a presidential hopeful, was guest at a local
Republican barbecue in Sullivan. Jenne, 14, and his Scout troop
were detailed to surround Nixon's table to keep the throngs away.
   ``Security wasn't like it is today,'' Jenne recalled. ``It was
pretty lax.''
   Nixon had taken just three or four bites when he had to leave.
   ``I saw (the sandwich) sitting there, so I just grabbed it,
plate and all,'' Jenne recalled.
   That partially eaten sandwich became Jenne's claim to fame. The
incident got newspaper coverage at the time and again, eight years
later, when Nixon was elected president.
   The sandwich, Jenne said, has been stored in a glass jar over
the years. The paper plate on which it rested, still sporting
barbecue stains, is between the pages of a folder which his mother,
Hazel, created especially for ``sandwich souvenirs.''
   Printed on the plate, in a 14-year-old's handwriting, are the
words ``This is the plate on which Vice President and future
President Nixon ate buffalo barbecue. Sept. 22, 1960.''
   The sandwich has survived weather-related power outages and once
falling on the floor.
   ``I think (the sandwich) has survived better than Nixon has,''
Mrs. Jenne said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scrubs became the first team in the Merry
Maids National Housecleaning Olympics as 12 teams of two maids each
vied in the vacuum cord curl, toilet bowl brush relay and
upholstery tool golf.
   About 560 Merry Maids franchise owners and managers, in Omaha
for a seminar, cheered on the finalists Friday, who had won the
right to compete by defeating other maids in local and regional
trials across the country.
   ``We do it (the games) to recognize our maids,'' said Dale
Peterson, a Merry Maids executive vice president. ``They're the key
to our success.''
   The competition came complete with bleachers, cheerleaders,
popcorn and peanuts and a twist on the traditional torch-lighting
ceremony.
   The two torch bearers raced into the Red Lion Hotel ballroom
carrying toilet bowl brushes and ``lit'' the crepe paper flames
that leapt from a toilet bowl on a marble pedestal.
   The gold medal winners were Marian Bosack and Marilyn Hadeen of
Council Bluffs, Iowa. Mary Hardway and Robin Moore of Newark, Ohio,
won the silver, while Jeannette Mooney and Danielle Sturtz of
Tempe, Ariz., won the bronze medal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like it or not, if you plan to work during
the winter season to qualify for a discounted ski pass in this
mountain resort town, you will have to attend Smile School.
   The Vail Chamber of Commerce has decided that all bellhops,
bartenders and others working in the service industry must complete
the $25, three-hour courtesy class before qualifying for the ski
pass.
   The program officially is called Guest Service Orientation, but
it quickly took the name Smile School _ the name of a
town-sponsored orientation program for Vail bus drivers and parking
attendants.
   Not everyone is smiling over the chamber's decision.
   ``Smile School is a wonderful idea so our guests will enjoy good
service, but the chamber of commerce went about it in the wrong
way,'' said Allison Sullivan, a bartender at Bart and Yeti's. ``It
really wasn't the $25 cost, but just the way they announced that
attendance was required for the discount like we were school
children.''
   Employers who didn't pick up the $25 cost for their employees
``would come off like a bad guy, and that wasn't fair to them,''
she said.
   The merchant pass for employees will remain $625 for those who
earn their Smile School certificate, and $725 for other community
residents, including workers who don't take the course.
   ``We feel that excellent service to our guests must be stressed
because we face a very important year at Vail, especially with the
world championships that will bring the top international skiers
here,'' said Shelbi Williams, chamber director.
</TEXT>
