<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TaxBill     10-22 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Bill,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$4.1 Billion Tax Bill Extends Some Benefits, Adds New Ones</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-The 100th Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the first lessons learned by a member
of Congress is that there's no better way to keep voters happy than
to cut their taxes.
   There's no money left in the federal treasury to grant any more
across-the-board tax reductions such as were approved in 1981. But
that doesn't prevent the lawmakers from granting targeted relief to
one group after another.
   That's exactly what they did in the tax bill that cleared its
final hurdle in Congress on Saturday. It now goes to President
Reagan, and sponsors predict he will sign it.
   The bill originally was designed to clear up confusing language
and correct errors in the landmark tax overhaul enacted in 1986.
But it was amended over and over to extend some expiring benefits,
add some new ones for selected groups, and raise taxes to finance
the benefits.
   The measure would have no effect on the federal deficit.
Although it would cut taxes by $4.1 billion over three years, it
would raise others by the same amount.
   And it is not just tax cuts and increases that were attached to
the bill. It includes a ``taxpayer's bill of rights'' to rein in
what some lawmakers view as an overly aggressive Internal Revenue
Service; for example, the agency would have to give 30 days' notice
before seizing bank accounts and other property, and would be
prohibited from promoting employees on the basis of how much they
collect.
   Some of the other provisions:
   _DIESEL: Wipe out a 1987 requirement that farmers, construction
companies and other tax-exempt, off-road users of diesel fuel pay
the federal tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and later apply for a refund.
   _MUTUAL FUNDS: For 1988 and 1989, permit owners of mutual fund
shares to deduct certain operating expenses of the fund without
regard to a general provision allowing deduction of only
miscellaneous expenses that exceed 2 percent of income.
   _HIGHER EDUCATION: Exempt from taxation interest earned on U.S.
savings bonds that are redeemed to finance a college or vocational
education, starting in 1990.
   _TUITION AID: Renew for 1988 an expired law allowing a worker to
avoid tax on up to $5,250 a year of employer-provided education
assistance. Graduate education would not qualify.
   _HOUSING: Extend through 1989 a tax credit for owners of newly
constructed low-income rental housing. Also, extend through 1989
and modify a tax exemption for bonds issued by state and local
governments to help low-income families buy their first home.
   _TOBACCO: Impose a tax of 45 cents per pound on pipe tobacco.
   _WRITERS: Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to
deduct work-related expenses even before a project produces income.
   _`HEIFER TAX': Permit livestock farmers to deduct expenses of
producing livestock before the animals begin generating income,
thus repealing what has become known as the ``heifer tax.''
   _ATHLETICS: Allow an 80 percent deduction for contributions to
college athletic scholarship funds even when such ``gifts''
guarantee a fan the privilege of buying a game ticket.
   _RESEARCH: Extend through 1989 a credit for increased spending
for research and experimentation.
   _JOB TRAINING: Extend through 1989 a credit under which the
government pays the first year of wages for certain newly hired
economically disadvantaged workers.
   _CONTRACTORS: Further restrict the ``completed-contract'' method
of accounting that allows defense contractors and most big
construction companies to delay taxes on part of their profits
until a project is completed. This change will raise $1.3 billion.
   _CORPORATIONS: Accelerate estimated tax payments from
corporations that switch from an annualized method of computation,
raising $869 million.
   _ALASKA CORPORATIONS: Repeal a provision that has allowed Alaska
Native corporations to sell some of their unused tax credits to
other companies; repeal will cost the Alaska companies $1 billion.
   _LIFE INSURANCE: Remove some of the tax advantages of using
single-premium life insurance as an investment. Loans from such
policies would be taxed as cash withdrawals; the new rules would
apply to policies whose cash value builds more quickly than one
paid through seven equal annual premiums. The change would cost
policyholders $345 million.
   _MAIL CARRIERS: Allow rural mail carriers to deduct 33.75 cents
for each mile a personal car is driven on a mail route; most people
are allowed 22.5 cents a mile for business-related mileage.
   _BUSINESS MEALS: Permit operators of offshore or Alaska oil rigs
and of some commercial vessels (but not luxury liners) to deduct
the full cost of meals provided to employees; most business may
deduct only 80 percent.
   _HOME SALE: Allow a surviving spouse to defer taxation on
profits from the sale of a principal home, just as though the
spouse had not died. Present law denies such a break if a spouse
dies after a home is sold and before a new one is built. Also, the
provision allowing a person over 55 to avoid tax on up to $125,000
of profits from the sale of a principal home in which he or she had
lived at least three of the last five years would be available to a
person who spends up to four of those five years in a nursing home.
   _HOME PHONE: Prohibit any person with a home-based business from
deducting any part of the base monthly telephone charge as a
business expense.
   _FARM MACHINERY: Tighten depreciation provisions for
single-purpose farm structures, such as poultry houses, and farm
machinery.
   _FARM INCOME: Expand a law allowing farmers to defer for one
year income from the drought-forced sale of livestock. Also, the
measure would ensure that farmers may defer taxes on payments
received as a result of drought-caused crop losses.
   _BANKS: Renew a tax break for healthy savings and loan
associations that take over failing associations, and extend the
benefit to banks.
   _HIGH-SPEED RAIL: Permit use of tax-exempt bonds to finance
certain high-speed rail facilities.
   _BLOOD DONORS: Permit states and blood-collection facilities to
require blood donors to list their Social Security numbers so they
can be traced if tests determine their blood is carrying the AIDS
virus.
   _AMISH: Exempt from Social Security taxes employees from Amish
and other sects with religious objections to the program;
self-employed Amish already are exempt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Opera     10-22 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Opera,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Met Forges Final Link In `Ring Cycle' Chain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire and flood consumed the stage of the
Metropolitan Opera House in the final scene of Wagner's
``Goetterdaemmerung,'' but instead of fleeing in panic, the
audience leapt to its feet and cheered.
   The triumphant premiere of the new production Friday night meant
that the nation's leading opera house had forged the final link in
its long-awaited new production of Wagner's epic ``Ring Cycle.''
   The sets and the lighting were among the most spectacular ever
seen at the Met and, at least as far as the heroine and the villain
were concerned, it seemed as if the company had even brought back
the much-lamented bygone Golden Era of Wagnerian singing.
   Soprano Hildegard Behrens, singing and acting with passion and
elegance as the noble Bruennhilde, consolidated her claim as a
worthy successor to the great Birgit Nilsson. She and bass Matti
Salminen as the baleful Hagen dominated the stage and easily
penetrated even the cruelest waves of sound that Wagner _ and the
Met orchestra _ could provide.
   Not for 13 seasons had the company performed this last and
longest (nearly six hours including two intermissions) of the four
operas in which Wagner intertwined Norse mythology and 19th century
German philosophy with sometimes muddled, but generally powerful,
results.
   ``Twilight of the Gods'' as the opera is called in English,
turns on Hagen's determination to get his hands on the magical gold
ring that has been the source of all the trouble since his father,
Alberich, stole it from the Rhinemaidens in the first opera, ``Das
Rheingold.''
   The plot twists might seem silly were they not redeemed by
Wagner's glorious music, which carries the audience through
contrivances like an amnesia-inducing potion and a magical helmet
that disguises Siegfried so Bruennhilde can't recognize her own
husband when he kidnaps her.
   The sets by Guenther Schneider-Siemssen have combined naturalism
with high-tech effects throughout the earlier operas and reach
their artistic peak in Act 3. The first scene, a forest clearing
where Hagen murders Siegfried, is strikingly realistic, the tableau
resembling a Flemish painting. Gil Wechsler's lighting moves subtly
from dappled sunlight to encroaching darkness as the hero's doom
approaches.
   But the real stage wizardry is saved for the finale, when
Bruennhilde's suicide in Siegfried's funeral pyre literally sets
the world ablaze, causes the Rhine to overflow, and even burns up
Valhalla, the kingdom of the Gods. All this is vividly brought to
life as the orchestra, splendidly conducted by James Levine, pours
out the final measures of the score.
   In a performance so strong it's a shame the biggest weakness was
the Siegfried of Toni Kramer. He seemed ill at ease on stage, his
medium-sized voice showed severe strain by Act 2, and he gave only
a workmanlike rendition of his wonderful final narrative. Baritone
Anthony Raffell failed to make much impression in the thankless
role of Gunther, Hagen's half-brother. Soprano Kathryn Harries did
better as Gunther's sister, Gutrune, but had trouble with her high
notes.
   In the small but vital role of Waltraute, Bruennhilde's sister,
mezzo Christa Ludwig _ who was singing in Ring Cycles 20 years ago
_ made a dazzling impression and provided a valuable link with a
tradition the Met is bidding to revive.
   ``Goetterdaemmerung'' will be performed several more times this
fall. In the spring, the Met will stage three complete Rings _ one
of them on successive Saturday afternoons in April for a nationwide
radio audience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Prices     10-22 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Prices,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meat And Bread Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia-Future, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meat prices rose Saturday and bread
prices will rise by 60 percent, the government said, two days after
an unpopular austerity program was amended to allow salary raises
for some workers.
   The Belgrade daily Politika Ekspres said the latest price
increases ``will drive the remaining shoppers out of meat markets''
and will further depress living standards.
   Thousands of Yugoslavs in recent weeks have protested rising
prices in a growing economic crisis in the communist nation.
   As of Saturday, prime quality steak cost $6.36 a pound in
Belgrade, up from $5.55. Ground meat rose from $2.21 to $3.39 a
pound.
   The cheapest type of bread, now available for 5 cents a pound,
will cost 8 cents when new bread prices take effect Sunday,
Politika Ekspres said.
   Statistics published here say living standards have dropped to
the level of the mid-1960s. Inflation is running as high as 217
percent.
   Meat prices were boosted considerably three weeks ago. Last
year, the government had to cancel sharp increases in bread prices
after widespread protests.
   The average monthly income in Yugoslavia is $100, and experts
say about 80 percent of it goes for food.
   Faced with increasing strikes and worker protests, Parliament on
Thursday eased an austerity program of wage cuts and price rises
introduced in May.
   The amendments allow wages increases of 140 percent to 152
percent this year, but only for workers in profitable companies and
in hard-pressed social services like health and education.
   Another Belgrade newspaper, Vecernje Novosti, said about half of
Yugoslav companies, employing more than 2 million workers, will not
be able to increase their wages because they are not making profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
