<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     10-22 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Reported In Good Spirits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's spirits improved Saturday
despite what doctors described as worsening kidney and liver
functions, a palace official said.
   Palace spokesman Kenji Maeda said Hirohito was unusually
talkative with aides and family members. His fever ebbed to 98.2 by
midday, one of the lowest since he fell seriously ill with
intestinal bleeding Sept. 19.
   By evening, however, the 87-year-old emperor's temperature rose
to 100 after doctors administered a blood transfusion of 0.84
pints, Maeda said.
   Hirohito has received 24.8 pints of blood since he fell ill.
   Hirohito's kidney and liver functions were worsening after
repeated transfusions, a senior palace official said.
   But the progression of his jaundice had stopped, and Hirohito's
anemia seemed to be improving, said the official, who spoke on the
condition he not be named.
   An anti-nuclear group protested widespread displays of reserve,
including cancellations of meetings and festivals in deference to
Hirohito's illness.
   ``These are taking place in disregard of ... the people's
sovereignty,'' the Japan Council Against Atomic and Hydrogen Bombs
said in a statement.
   ``This unusual state of affairs goes hand in hand with a
strengthening of the Japan-U.S. military alliance and a military
buildup. Where is it leading the people?''
</TEXT>
