<DOCNO> AP881022-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle-Campaign 1stLd-Writethru a0564 10-22 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Campaign, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle: ``One-Liners Say a Lot''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, removing extraneous material</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``One-liners say a lot,'' says Dan Quayle,
contending that voters have been well informed this year even
though the presidential campaigns have often aimed merely for
catchy television ``sound bites.''
   ``There are a lot of subtleties communicated with a sound
bite,'' the brief TV clip on the evening news, he said. ``People
receive messages.''
   Voters, Quayle said, can receive a complex message from a simple
one-liner, especially when such elements as body language are added
in.
   While Quayle said television coverage of the campaign, the
dominant medium for most Americans, has occasionally lacked
substance, he also said ``the information is out there'' for voters
to make up their minds.
   Both of the presidential compaigns spend millions of dollars on
television advertising, and they arrange candidate appearances and
speeches with an eye toward getting a particular few seconds on the
news. But Quayle said that isn't all bad.
   ``What you have right now is you have to get a story across and
the temptation is to say `OK, we've got a message today we want to
get across on our own terms and nobody else's,''' Quayle said.
   ``That's a pretty good strategy,'' he said. ``You can't fault
the strategy.''
   ``The people, by and large, know a lot about all four of us,''
he said. ``It's more oriented to one-liners, but, you know,
one-liners say a lot.
   ``Let's not minimize the importance of one-liners.''
   Quayle made his comments Friday night in an interview as his
campaign plane returned to Washington after he spent a week
stumping in the Midwest and South.
   In the interview, Quayle was mildly critical of the coverage of
the campaign but generally satisfied that voters had been told what
they need in order to make a choice.
   ``I found out that, at least in my own case, sometimes I've
given what I think have been very susbtantative speeches. ... There
doesn't seem to be much interest in covering it,'' he said.
   ``The question is, have we been well-served? I think we know a
lot about Michael Dukakis and George Bsh. I think they really have
a very good idea of the four candidates.''
   Quayle said he's now more comfortable as a national candidate
because ``a national campaign is now something that's more behind
me than ahead of me.''
   That comfort level is increased because he's now settling into
the traditional role of a vice presidential candidate rather than a
lightning rod for controversy, he said.
   That point was underscored, he said, by a telephone call he
received from his wife, Marilyn, late in the week.
   ``She said `you must really be giving great speeches, having
great crowds, doing all the right things, because I haven't heard a
thing about you out here,''' he said. ``Welcome to the traditional
role of the vice presidential campaign.''
   Quayle said both of the presidential campaigns have dealt with
substantative issues.
   ``There have been a number of speeches, a number of debates,
probably too many speeches,'' he said. ``The information is out
there. The question is on how this information gets communicated.
   ``The question then becomes, what is being communicated? Is it
the 15-second sound bite?
   ``I'll be interested to find out what we've learned from this,''
he said. ``I think we've got to rethink it on both sides.
   ``You have to look at how television is used by both
campaigns,'' he said. ``It is very difficult to do in a
substantative way, even though there have been substantative
speeches.
   ``I'm sure we'll go back and there'll be new benchmarks,
there'll be new standards, maybe some old standards will be thrown
away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Swindall Bjt   10-22 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swindall, Bjt,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers See Two Sides To Congressman's Hurry-up Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall is attempting to beat an
Election Day deadline with his one-man, rush-to-justice defense in
a federal perjury trial that will climax one of the country's most
bitter congressional elections.
   If everything goes as expected, the two-term Republican
congressman will deliver his opening argument in U.S. District
Court on Monday, just one week after his indictment was handed up
and just 15 days before the Nov. 8 election.
   Swindall, a lawyer, is representing himself in the perjury case
and hopes a quick acquittal will bring victory at the polls.
   He has admitted to a mistake in judgment in negotiating an
$850,000 loan last year with an undercover agent posing as a
financier, but denies criminal wrongdoing. Eventually, Swindall
accepted a $150,000 check from a middleman, then returned it
uncashed.
   The 10 perjury charges brought against Swindall stem from his
testimony before a grand jury in February. Among other things,
Swindall testified he could not recall any mention of drug money;
tapes of the meetings have the agent saying the loan money was
probably drug-related.
   Swindall is facing the same challenger he did in 1986 in his bid
for a third term in the House. He calls it a race between ``a
Dukakis liberal and a Bush conservative.''
   Voters in the suburbs east of Atlanta will choose between
Swindall and Democrat Ben Jones, a one-time ``Dukes of Hazzard'' TV
star who has had to answer repeated questions from Swindall about
his admitted bout with alcoholism.
   Though Swindall demanded the speedy trial to obtain a verdict
before the election, he has stressed his disadvantage in manpower
and time to prepare for the trial, saying he will just have to rely
on the ``ol' innocent defense.''
   In fact, he will have more going for him, said lawyer Guy Davis,
a former policeman and prosecutor who was the Republican nominee
for governor in 1986. Davis has been a critic of Swindall but
expressed admiration for his tactics in the case.
   Davis said he has seen both laymen and lawyers successfully
defend themselves.
   ``Many defendants found that there was an advantage in that the
jury was continously being exposed to the defendant himself while
he conducts the trial,'' he said.
   If Swindall is a good courtroom performer, he said, he will be
able to impress his case on the jurors ``from the time the trial
starts, and not just from the time he takes the witness stand.''
   But Robert Fierer, who has handled a string of high-profile
criminal cases and represents another defendant in the
money-laundering probe, said that while Swindall may get the
underdog's sympathy from the jury, he is sacrificing some
potentially important options in rushing to trial.
   ``He really has given up investigative time, the time to go out
and find witnesses, to get prepared on witnesses, and that sort of
thing,'' Fierer said. Davis, however, noted that Swindall has had
access to transcripts of his meetings with the undercover agent for
some time, ``so he's probably, no doubt, well-prepared to go to
trial. And I think probably it is a wise thing for him to do.''
   And Davis said some pre-trial skirmishing over what can be used
in court and demands for information are not as crucial to Swindall
because ``in this case, the facts are fairly simple.''
   If the trial starts Monday, Swindall also gives up time for
pre-trial hearings that could have helped his defense, especially
on his claims that U.S. Attorney Robert Barr, also a Republican, is
promoting his career at Swindall's expense.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Vining ruled that Swindall may not
present those claims to the jury without conducting a pre-trial
hearing on whether Barr could be subpoenaed. Swindall hasn't
officially told the judge whether he wants the hearing, but he has
indicated he will not permit a delay in the trial.
   It will be up to the jury to decide whether Swindall can
reconcile the tapes of his meetings with the undercover agent with
his later grand jury testimony.
   Swindall has vowed to show his answers were not deceitful
because he simply could not remember everything said in the
negotiations.
   The 38-year-old congressman has had to curtail campaigning,
saying the trial has become the campaign's most important factor.
   His pre-indictment polls, he said, found a dead heat. Jones'
campaign manager, Maren Hesla, disagreed.
   ``Congressman Swindall has attempted to make the verdict the
election, but that's just not the case,'' Ms. Hesla said. ``We
enjoyed an 18-point lead prior to the indictment.''
   Jones, who has acknowledged a conviction for assault on his wife
during the days he was battling alcoholism, has been quiet about
his opponent's criminal case. Ms. Hesla acknowledged that Jones has
lost news media attention because of the focus on Swindall's case.
``We're doing what we can to be out there meeting the voters right
now,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-ReaganText     10-22 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan Text,890</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of President Reagan's weekly
radio address delivered Saturday from Camp David, Md.:
   My fellow Americans, Abraham Lincoln once said, ``You can't fool
all of the people all of the time.'' Well, this week, our liberal
friends have been trying to prove him wrong.
   They've charged that our record of lowering your taxes, ending
runaway inflation, and igniting the longest peacetime economic
expansion ever, has been bad for middle class working Americans.
   Well, it's time to remind them of a few facts.
   For example, the misery index: the miserly index was an election
year gimmick they cooked up for the 1976 campaign by adding the
unemployment and inflation rates. It came to 13.4 percent in 1976,
and they declared that no one had a right to seek reelection with a
misery index that high.
   Well, four years later, in the 1980 campaign, they didn't
mention the misery index, perhaps because it had grown to almost 21
percent. And this year, they still aren't mentioning it. Under us,
it's dropped to under 10 percent.
   Our liberal friends have been hopping around the country,
charging that real family income is no higher today than it was 20
years ago. Now, in fact, it's 14 percent higher. But why would they
bring family income up at all? After all, between 1977 and 1981 _
maybe you can guess why I picked those years _ the typical American
family's income, after taking out inflation, fell seven percent.
   Think of what it would mean to you and your family if somebody
were to cut your family's paychecks by that much today.
   Think of how much less you could buy at the grocery store, the
clothes you couldn't get for your children, how much less you could
put in the plate at your church or synagogue each week.
   And then, think of this: since 1981, when we came to office, the
typical family's income, after taking out inflation, has soared
more than 10 percent.
   One place you can see what this change means to you is in
housing. Our liberal friends have been talking a great deal about
affordable housing recently. Don't they remember that in 1980, as
housing prices and interest rates skyrocketed together, one of the
few times in history that's happened, and real family incomes
plummeted, the American dream of owning a home almost went down for
the count.
   And the top housing official of the previous administration
finally threw up his hands in despair and said, ``For many
hard-working families, housing is growing beyond their reach,''
   Yes, according to real estate industry economists in 1980, the
average American family made just over three-fourths of what it
needed to buy a home. Today, with interest rates half of what they
were and inflation under control, the typical American family makes
over 110 percent of what it needs to buy home.
   Renters are also doing better. When the liberals left office,
the national vacancy rates for apartments in the price range of low
and medium income families were around five percent, which means it
had become hard for low and medium income Americans to find an
apartment. Today, these national vacancy rates are around eight
percent, and it's the landlords who are having to wait longer to
find tenants.
   Add this all up and you see that we have more, much more,
affordable housing today then we had eight years ago.
   You'd think all these facts would give our liberal opponents
pause, but apparently not.
   When we note that since our expansion began, America has created
more than 18 million new jobs, that unemployment is nearly the
lowest it's been in 14 years, and that a greater proportion of
Americans are at work today than ever before in our history, the
liberals blandly respond that what we need are ``good jobs at good
wages.''
   Perhaps they believe that most Americans have bad jobs. I don't
believe that, and to tell the truth, I find remarks that put down
honest occupations _ yes, including short-order chefs _ offensive,
and I expect you do too. In any event, overall, job for job, the
jobs created since our expansion began pay more than the jobs that
existed before.
   The liberals charge that we've given tax breaks to the wealthy,
but when we came to office, the wealthy were paying 19.3 percent of
the federal individual income tax revenues. Now it's 26 percent.
   The charges go on and on, but the truth remains the same. No
matter how you look at it, the last time they were in office, the
liberals clobbered the American middle class and we stopped them.
   Some are calling this last-ditch opposition campaign an attempt
at ``class warfare.''
   So, what's new? Our liberal friends have been at war with
America's middle class for years. Now they want you to turn the
other cheek, but will they just take that as an opportunity to
really let you have it.
   Mainstream America is in better shape today than it's ever been.
Why would we ever want to put it back in the hands of those who
almost turned out its lights?
   Until next week, thanks for listening and God bless you.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
