<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Radio     10-22 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Radio,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Hits Dukakis on Jobs, Byrd Says Democrats Champion of
Middle Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan ridiculed presidential
candidate Michael Dukakis' campaign theme of ``good jobs at good
wages'' on Saturday, asserting it is a cover for the belief ``that
most Americans have bad jobs.''
   President Reagan's weekly radio address from Camp David, Md.,
followed the pattern of recent weeks in which he has launched an
entirely partisan attack against the ``liberals'' in this year's
election campaign.
   While Reagan contended that the Republican Party was the
champion of the middle class, Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd
of West Virginia also claimed that honor in the Democratic response.
   ``As majority leader of the Senate Democrats, I take pride in
the work of the 100th Congress. We have done our duty. We have
addressed your concerns. We have listened to the people,'' Byrd
said in an address relayed only hours after the Congress had
adjourned for the year.
   The senator said the Democratic-led Congress fulfilled a
specific agenda: ``check and balance a White House that seemed to
have lost its way. We delivered despite two years of
confrontation.''
   In his address, Reagan did not mention Dukakis or the GOP
candidate, Vice President George Bush, by name, but his target was
clear.
   Using his favorite catch-word for the Democratic Party, Reagan
asserted that ``our liberal friends'' in the campaign have no
response to the nation's robust economy or its low unemployment
rate.
   Reagan and Bush have repeatedly boasted that ``more than 18
million new jobs'' have been created during the economic expansion.
   But Dukakis has countered with the charge that many of the jobs
created during the Reagan presidency have been minimum-wage
positions, such as those in the fast-food industry.
   ``The liberals blandly respond that what we need are good jobs
at good wages,'' Reagan said. ``Perhaps they actually believe that
most American have bad jobs.''
   ``I don't believe that. And to tell the truth, I find remarks
that put down honest occupations _ and that's including short order
chefs _ offensive. And I expect you do too,'' Reagan added.
   ``The jobs created since our expansion began pay more than the
jobs that existed before,'' he said.
   Reagan also tried to counter Democratic charges that his
administration has given tax breaks to the wealthy by asserting
that the middle class has flourished under his administration.
   Charging that ``our liberal friends have been at war with the
American middle class for years,'' Reagan argued that ``mainstream
America is in better shape today than it's ever been. Why would we
want to put it back in the hands of those who almost turned out its
lights?''
   For his part, Byrd contended that the Democratic Congress has
dealt with ``the problems that people talk about when they sit
around the kitchen table.''
   Byrd said the Congress had expanded Medicare to include
catastrophic health insurance, fought for parental leave and child
care bills, and tried to obtain ``an increase in the minimum wage
despite White House opposition.''
   ``Harry Truman once said that ``polls are like sleeping pills
designed to lull voters into sleeping on election day,'' Byrd said.
``Don't let the polls lull you to sleep. Don't let the political
hucksters pick the next president.
   ``Look beneath the surface. Look to the record. Vote for the
future. Remember that America is always at its best when we face
our problems and never stand still,'' he said.
</TEXT>
