<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrappedWhales-Chronology     10-22 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Whales-Chronology,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Events in Attempts to Free Whales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of major events in the attempts to free the
three trapped whales in Barrow, Alaska:
   Oct. 13 _ The California gray whales were discovered trapped in
the ice east of Point Barrow. They apparently became stuck a week
before. Biologists were unable to contact an icebreaker to give aid.
   Oct. 14 _ The whales continued to swim several hundred feet
offshore, using two holes in the ice to breathe. Biologists
believed time was running out for the grays as nighttime
temperatures dropped to 13 degrees below zero, threatening to
shrink the whales' breathing space. Efforts failed again to contact
an icebreaking ship.
   Oct. 18 _ A biologist said one whale may have pneumonia, as an
Alaska Army National Guard Skycrane helicopter went to tow a
185-ton Hovercraft-type icebreaking barge 200 miles northwest to
the whales. President Reagan telephoned with his support.
   Oct. 19 _ Eskimos cut new holes in ice, but the barge effort was
hampered by shallow water. Biologists said the whales' health
appeared to be stabilized, and that they were handling their
captivity better than first believed.
   Oct. 20 _ The barge began its journey but moved only about six
miles through sand bars, mud and shallow water. Two Minnesota
brothers-in-law arrive with de-icers to enlarge breathing holes for
whales.
   Oct. 21 _ One of the whales, nicknamed ``Bone,'' disappeared and
was presumed dead. Rescuers tried ``Plan B:'' A five-ton concrete
``bullet'' wielded by a helicopter loaned by the Alaska Army
National Guard. Easterly wind opened ``leads,'' or open water,
through the ice within four miles of the whales. The Soviet Union
offered an icebreaker to help in the rescue.
   Oct. 22 _ Eskimos using chain saws had led the whales almost a
half-mile closer to open water by carving a string of 24 breathing
holes in the ice. The Skycrane dropping its ``bullet'' had punched
four 15-to-20-foot holes in the ice at 75-yard intervals, but a
massive pressure ridge of ice stood in the way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     10-22 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Warns Texas Voters Against Ticket Splitting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GILMER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen warned his fellow Texans on
Saturday against ticket splitting to support him for the Senate and
Republican George Bush for president in hopes of giving powerful
jobs to two men with ties to the state.
   ``Some Republicans ... are trying to peddle the notion that you
can vote twice for Texas,'' Bentsen told a union audience in
Beaumont as he stumped with Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis. ``Have you heard that one?''
   It was a rare acknowledgement of the political problem tied to
his dual candidacies for vice president and re-election to the
Senate from Texas.
   ``A vote for George Bush is a vote for Dan Quayle, and a vote
for Dan Quayle sure isn't a vote for Lloyd Bentsen. A vote for
George Bush or Dan Quayle makes no sense if you care for Texas,''
he said.
   ``A vote for George Bush is a vote against a strong energy
policy that will bring this state back,'' he said.
   Under Texas law, Bentsen is allowed to run for both the vice
presidency and the Senate. He has said he would resign from the
Senate if he and Dukakis win, but he was staying in that race
because resigning would automatically hand the seat to Republican
opponent Beau Boulter for six years. A resignation, on the other
hand, would force a special election.
   Bentsen made his comments at a joint rally with Dukakis in a
packed hall owned by the local pipefitters union, whose members are
highly dependant on the oil and gas industry. East Texas is a
traditionally Democratic part of the state and the Dukakis-Bentsen
ticket needs to win big there to have any chance of carrying the
state and its 29 electoral votes on Nov. 8.
   Mike McCurry, Bentsen's press secretary, said the senator spoke
up because some news editorials in Texas had suggested that Texans
support the Republicans for president and Bentsen for the Senate,
instead of his Republican opponent Beau Boulter.
   Some Bush supporters, who also like Bentsen, have been making
that suggestion to boost ticket splitting. The polls show Bentsen a
handy winner in his Senate race but the Democrats behind in the
presidential race and they don't want Texas supporters of Bentsen
to feel satisfied by just supporting him for the Senate.
   After campaigning together in Beaumont, Dukakis and Bentsen went
their separate ways and Bentsen traveled north to Gilmer for the
annual ``Yamboree'' celebrating the year's crop of yams before
heading on to Missouri.
   On a stage decorated with bushels of yams and some pumpkins,
Bentsen told a crowd of several hundred people, not to listen to
Republican ads claiming that the Democrats wanted to take away
their guns and were weak on defense. He took particular umbrage at
a Republican Party ad featuring former test pilot Chuck Yeager
saying the Democrats were bad for the defense industry, which is a
major employer in Texas.
   ``I decided he set some of those high altitude records and
forgot to turn on his oxygen,'' Bentsen said.
   Orange-lettered signs proclaimed ``Yammin' with
Dukakis-Bentsen'' as the senator spoke and then rode around town in
a convertible waving at the friendly thousands attending the
festival.
   There was some disagreement in the campaign entourage as whether
there was any real difference between yams and sweet potatoes, and
Bentsen was asked what he thought the difference was.
   ``Well, I don't know,'' he said. ``But I'm yam proud to be
here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
