<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudioOpening     10-22 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Studio Opening,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cleavers Attend Grand Opening Of Florida Studio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eddie Haskell joined Wally, June and the
Beaver before the two-story Cleaver home to mark the grand opening
of Universal Studios Florida, where ``The New Leave It To Beaver''
series will be produced.
   ``Hey, we're really excited about being here,'' Tony Dow, who
plays Wally Cleaver, told reporters Friday. ``The set looks great,
don't you think?''
   Standing before the familiar Cleaver home, which was trucked in
from Universal Studios in Hollywood, executive producer Brian
Levant introduced the cast members as they emerged one by one
through the front door.
   Mindful of tradition, Levant said as he announced the members of
the original cast: ``Barbara Billingsley ... Tony Dow ... Ken
Osmond .. and Jerry Mathers as the Beaver.''
   The arrival of the show at Universal Studios Florida was marked
by the ceremonial mounting of the Cleavers' house number _ 211.
   The numbers were hammered in and removed three times for the
benefit of TV crews who may have missed it.
   ``This is the day we've looked forward to for many, many years,
the beginning of production at Universal Studios Florida,'' studio
president Steven Lew said.
   Everything except the sidewalk (painted plywood) in front of the
Cleaver house came from Hollywood _ even the brown leaves (real
leaves) that were strewn about to simulate autumn.
   Once inside, the cast wandered around their home.
   Mathers looked through curtains to the back yard.
   ``Gee, here we are in Florida and we have the same neighbors,''
he said, looking out at a wall mural of homes and yards.
   Much of the 444-acre movie-television complex is still being
built. But ``The New Leave It To Beaver,'' which airs on cable's
SuperStation TBS, will produce 19 episodes this season in the
22,000-square-foot sound stage, which means the cast and crew will
be in Central Florida until March.
   The original ``Leave It To Beaver'' began in October 1957 on
CBS, then moved to ABC in October 1958, where the sitcom ran until
September 1963. Twenty years later, CBS aired a TV-movie titled
``Still the Beaver,'' which in turn spawned a series of the same
title on the Disney channel in 1984.
   Disney droped the Cleavers after two seasons, but Ted Turner
soon ordered 74 episodes for his cable station, which could keep
the series on the air until the early 1990s.
   Economy was a big factor in the move east. Michael Houbrick, a
spokesman for the show, said last season might have been the show's
last if it had to continue production on the West Coast, where
union wages are considerably higher than in Florida.
   The cast has nothing but praise for local hospitality and the
Universal facility. The studios in California were ``musty'' and
leaked, Mathers said.
   ``Every time it rained we had to move from one set to another.''
   Levant, however, said he sees few differences between Hollywood
East and West.
   ``We've still got to hide the palm trees when we go outside,
same as California.''
</TEXT>
