<2ND_LINE>AM-Barricaded Nuns,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuns At Convent Split By Dispute Remain In Prayer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother superior and five
Carmelite nuns who rebelled against her by barricading themselves
in their monastery have extended their period of seclusion, a nun
at the monastery said Saturday.
   The nuns locked themselves in the infirmary at the Monastery of
the Most Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel on Oct. 4. They fear
expulsion for opposing liberalizations at the cloister, including
the introduction of sweets, radio and television.
   Mother Theresa Hewitt says the dispute centers on the five nuns'
refusal to obey her. There are 13 nuns at the monastery.
   On Thursday, Mother Hewitt and Sister John of the Cross, one of
the five nuns, announced they would not speak to the media for two
days while both sides prayed for an end to the dispute.
   Sister Maria, a member of the Carmel who does not live at the
monastery, said Mother Hewitt has extended the period of seclusion
and prayer until Monday. The barricaded nuns agreed, she said.
   ``Mother Theresa wants the media to stay away and they all want
to get some rest,'' Sister Maria said.
