<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FranceFashion     10-22 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France Fashion,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montana Perfects A-Line Chic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claude Montana perfected his A-line chic and
Givenchy turned out his peppiest clothes in several seasons during
Saturday shows for next summer's ready-to-wear.
   Jean-Paul Gaultier's collection drew gasps and occasional
laughter with designs that ranged from a bawdy-house look to a
traveling circus act.
   Everything was long and beautiful by Montana, who showed only a
few skirts between trousers shaped like fluid inverted cones. He
also showed an occasional pair of wide, cuffed linen shorts.
   He kept to a muted tone of greys, browns and dusty pinks. The
high-waisted trousers he has done before but they never looked
better.
   Montana showed silk jumpsuits and flowing skirts with tops
draped in silk chiffon fichus, sometimes off the shoulder.
   Some toppers had floppy lapels, others had swooped, stitched
necklines and natural shoulderlines.
   The sophisticated outfits also had vest fronts with open backs
crossed by straps.
   Everything was sleek and easy. Jackets often had a long flared
look from an easily fitted bodice. Square-necked sundress tops were
like trapeze dresses over pants.
   While all the day clothes were dressy, evening clothes were
anything but show-off. Usually in austere black, they had lacquered
lace and net cut-outs in the bodices over swirling chiffon skirts.
   Givenchy delivered a collection to keep his Palm Beach-to-Paris
clients happy. There were short skirts and pants or skirt suits
came out with a snug silhouette.
   These silk, smooth wool and pique outfits looked peppy with very
wide, white piping all over, creating a clean look in navy with
white or yellow. Chunky or big pastille buttons also brightened up
the scene.
   With circular necks and slightly blousing tops, the silk
flower-print dresses were completely Givenchy. Even more striking
were the widely-striped silks with stand-out capped sleeves, square
necks and straight short skirts.
   Jean-Paul Gaultier threw caution to the wind after showing more
conventional clothes last season. He sees the upcoming nineties as
naughty, with lacy corsets, jackets open to reveal bosoms and shiny
tight pants.
   There was a full line of underwear dressing including a
multicolored girdle tunic and a clinging girdle dress with a bra
top.
   The finale was based on multi-suspenders and garters covering
the colorful elasticized jersey or satin body suits underneath.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
