<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     10-22 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Police Stations; Opposition Criticizes New
Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked two small
police stations in the south with machine guns and anti-tank
rockets, killing a corporal and wounding a local farmer, police
said Saturday.
   They were the first significant terrorist actions since
right-wing President Augusto Pinochet lost an Oct. 5 referendum on
extending his rule to 1997.
   According to a national police statement, eight guerrillas
opened fire Friday night with machine guns and M-16 rifles on a
small frontier post in Los Quenes, in the Andes foothills 20 miles
east of the city of Curico.
   The guerrillas then set a police building afire, destroying it
and a police jeep, the statement said. It said the gunfire killed a
corporal, Juvenal Vargas, and wounded a farmer visiting the post,
Fernando Garcia.
   An hour earlier, other guerrillas fired two anti-tank rockets at
another police post in Pichipellahuen, 55 miles southwest of the
town of Traiguen, the communique said. There were no injuries
reported in the attack.
   The communique blamed both attacks on the communist Manuel
Rodriguez Patriotic Front.
   A spokeswoman for a dissident faction of the front called
foreign news agencies in Santiago to claim responsibility for the
actions, saying they represented the start of a ``national
patriotic war.''
   Interior Minister Carlos Caceres called the police officer's
death ``an extremely cold terrorist act'' and called on Chileans
``to understand that this country wants to achieve democracy on a
peaceful level.''
   Caceres was named Friday, when Pinochet replaced half of his
Cabinet's 16 members in a shake-up prompted by Pinochet's
800,000-ballot loss in his bid to extend his term.
   The 72-year-old army commander seized power in a 1973 coup.
   Under the constitution, Pinochet remains in power until March
1990. The winner of open elections planned for December 1989 will
take over.
   While swearing in his new ministers, Pinochet firmly rejected
opposition calls to step down early and for consitutional reforms.
   Opposition leaders said his declaration and new Cabinet choices
dashed their hopes for prompt negotiations on the reforms.
   `The Cabinet is the same, only the names are different,'' said
Andres Zaldivar, vice-president of the centrist Christian
Democratic Party, the country's largest. ``It doesn't ... reflect
the feeling of the immense majority of Chileans who voted `no' on
Oct. 5.''
   Zaldivar, however, called on the opposition's ranks to ``keep a
cool head and firm nerves'' and not to resort to violent actions.
The coalition has repeatedly condemned leftist terrorist actions,
saying they provide an excuse for government repression.
   Ricardo Lagos, a prominent Socialist, noted that two army
generals, Public Works Minister Bruno Siebert and Economy Minister
Manuel Concha, and a retired navy admiral, Defense Minister
Patricio Carvajal, were retained while generals from the air force
and national police were ousted.
   The air force and national police are considered more
politically moderate than the navy or Pinochet's fiercely loyal
army.
</TEXT>
