<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Aronson     10-22 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Aronson,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Minnesota Rabbi David Aronson Dies At Age 96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rabbi David Aronson, former president of the
Rabbinical Assembly of America, has died after a short illness. He
was 96.
   ``He was one of the leading rabbis, nationally, in the last 60
years,'' said Rabbi Kassel Abelson, Aronson's successor at Beth El
Synagogue in the Minneapolis suburb of St. Louis Park.
   ``His work was very important, especially where it concerned
Jewish annulments and divorces,'' Abelson said. ``His book, `The
Jewish Way of Life,' published in 1945, has become a classic and
has been reprinted many times.''
   Aronson was born in Russia in 1892 and grew up in New York. He
attended New York University, Columbia University and the Jewish
Theological Seminary in New York.
   After ordination in 1919, Aronson served congregations in Salt
Lake City and Duluth, Minn., before joining Beth El in 1924. From
1948 to 1950, he was president of the Rabbinical Assembly of
America, an assembly of 1,200 Conservative rabbis.
   Aronson, who died Thursday, is survived by his wife, Bertha, of
Los Angeles, and two sons.
   A funeral service was scheduled for Sunday.
</TEXT>
