<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SecretClient     10-22 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Secret Client,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Million-Dollar Reward Offered For Identity Of Secret Client _ If</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of a man who was killed
in an unsolved hit-and-run are offering as much as $1 million to
anyone with information leading to the driver's identity.
   But the family says that before it can pay off, it first must
win a $6 million lawsuit against the driver, and his identity
apparently is known only to one person, an attorney who has won
court permission to keep it secret because of lawyer-client
privilege.
   That lawsuit is pending in Palm Beach County Circuit Court,
while state and private investigators continue trying to track down
the driver of the car.
   The suit was filed in February over the March 9, 1986, crash
that killed Mark Baltes in Palm Beach.
   Attorney Barry Krischer says the driver approached him for
counsel the day after the accident and he has steadfastly refused
to publicly identify him.
   On Oct. 12, Circuit Judge Timothy Poulton said Krischer did not
have to reveal that information because it is protected by
attorney-client confidentiality.
   ``This criminal is out there laughing at the system, hiding
behind the attorney-client privilege,'' says Joseph Farish,
attorney for Baltes' family. He devised the reward plan, announced
Friday, ``in order to make incentive for someone to come forward
and expedite this mystery.''
   Farish conceded that if someone comes forward with information
leading to the driver's identity, the tipster would have to wait
for a favorable jury verdict in the lawsuit.
   Richard Lubin, who represents Krischer, said he is indifferent
to Farish's tactics, as long as Farish does not trample on the
judge's ruling.
   ``It's really not my concern as long as he and everyone else
respects the attorney-client privilege,'' Lubin said.
   ``Anything that Mr. Farish or the Baltes family will do to help
us is welcome,'' said Chief Assistant State Attorney Ken Selvig.
``If this helps, we welcome it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
