<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     10-22 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Announces Release of 25 Iranian Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Saturday it will release 25
Iranian prisoners of war, but the two countries traded accusations
over the POW issue.
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted a Foreign Ministry
spokesman as saying the new release will raise to 645 the number of
sick and aging Iranian prisoners who have been freed.
   According to the International Red Cross, Iran holds 50,182
Iraqi POWs and Iraq holds 19,284 Iranians. But U.N. officials and
diplomats place the figures much higher, saying Iran holds
60,000-70,000 and Iraq 30,000-50,000.
   The Iraqi spokesman said the International Committee of the Red
Cross was asked to send a delegation to organize the new
repatriation, according to the news agency report monitored in
Nicosia.
   It said he called on Iran to reciprocate and claimed that Iran
``had all along dealt with the POW issue as a political one in
order to exploit it for the purposes of Iran's expansionist
policies.''
   A Tehran Radio commentary on Saturday welcomed Iraq's planned
release of prisoners but said real progress on the issue would only
come through quicker peace negotiations.
   It also accused Iraq of waffling on the issue, claiming Irdaq
first said it would not exchange prisoners within the framework of
U.N. Resolution 598 but later supported elements of that plan.
   The resolution is the basis for the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the
8-year-long war.
   The commentary, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in
London, said Iran was ready to exchange prisoners of war.
</TEXT>
