<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   10-22 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0609,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Wound 12 Palestinians In Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4: The bombing...refugee camps. with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with new death toll in Israeli raid. Pick up 5th pvs, The
army. ADDS 2 grafs at bottom to UPDATE with Kahane rally.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops shot and wounded 12 Palestinians on
Saturday in scattered clashes in the occupied territories, hospital
officials said. The army said a soldier was injured when he was
struck in the head by a rock.
   Also Saturday, 21-year-old Lt. Moti Shtaier died of wounds
suffered Wednesday when a suicide car bomb exploded in southern
Lebanon, the army said. His death raised the number of Israeli
troops killed in the explosion to eight. Two other soldiers were
hospitalized in critical condition.
   The bombing prompted Israeli air raids over southern Lebanon
Friday that killed 21 people and injured 34. Police initially said
16 people were killed but reported five more bodies were found in
rubble in the southeastern Lebanese town of Mashgara, one of the
main targets of the raids.
   Most of Saturday's rioting in the occupied territories was
confined to the Gaza Strip, where 650,000 Palestinians live, many
in refugee camps.
   The army placed curfews on Gaza's Nusseirat refugee camp and a
Gaza City neighborhood after violent protests, a military spokesman
said. Hospital officials said troops shot a 23-year-old resident in
the leg with a plastic bullet.
   The spokesman confirmed only one of the 12 wounded, identifying
him as a 16-year-old Gaza City boy shot and wounded by a plastic
bullet.
   Demonstrators stoned the army headquarters in Gaza's Jabaliya
refugee camp, an Arab reporter said. Soldiers responded with
plastic bullets, shooting and wounding a 20-year-old man in the
leg, the reporter and hospital officials said.
   The hospital officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said another Jabaliya man in his 20s was severely beaten by
club-wielding soldiers.
   In Gaza's town of Rafah, protesters burned tires at the open-air
market and hurled stones, slightly injuring a soldier, the reporter
said. Troops fired tear gas and plastic bullets to disperse the
crowd, shooting and wounding a 13-year-old boy in the leg and a
46-year-old man in the hand, the reporter said.
   Five others were shot and wounded by plastic bullets in other
protests, the reporter said.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, troops fired live ammunition to
disperse a crowd, wounding a 15-year-old Palestinian in the leg and
a 16-year-old in the stomach, hospital officials said. The
officials said an 18-year-old Palestinian from Salfit village was
brought to the hospital with a bullet wound to the stomach.
   The 10-month Palestinian revolt against Israeli rule of the
territories, captured from Jordan and Egypt in 1967 Middle East
War, has claimed the lives of 301 Palestinians and six Israelis.
   In Jerusalem, some 500 supporters of U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane
held a rally Saturday night to protest the exclusion of the
ultra-right-wing parliament member from the upcoming elections Nov.
1. The parliament's Central Elections Committee barred Kahane from
running for office because of his racist views.
   ``Arabs are a cancer in our midst,'' Kahane told the crowd, who
chanted, ``Death to the Arabs'' and waved yellow flags with the
Kahane emblem, a fist inside a black Star of David. Kahane
advocates expelling all Arabs from Israel.
</TEXT>
