<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LandSwap     10-22 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Land Swap,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Approves Indian School Land Swap</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0645 to delete extraneous paragraph.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stage has been set for a complex land swap
involving the 111-acre Phoenix Indian School campus and more than
100,000 acres of Florida swampland.
   Congress approved legislation concerning the swap on Thursday.
   The bill authorizes the Interior Department to dispose of the
school, which the Reagan administration wants to close because of
declining enrollments.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative wing of
Congress, has described the downtown Phoenix land as perhaps the
most valuable undeveloped piece of urban real estate in the West.
Under the plan, the Collier family interests of Florida will get
68.4 acres of the Phoenix property in exchange for the Florida
acreage and a cash payment of at least $34.9 million.
   The transaction also calls for the Veterans Administration to
get 11.5 acres of the school property to expand its Phoenix
hospital; Phoenix to get 20 acres for a park; and Arizona to get
4.5 acres for a veterans home. The rest of the land is tied up in
road rights-of-way.
   The money paid by the Colliers will be placed into a trust fund
for the education of Indians in Arizona.
   The Florida land will be used to provide a buffer around the
Everglades and to provide habitat for endangered species, such as
the Florida panther.
   The House voted 316-32 approval of a package of bills in which
the Phoenix deal was included.
   The measure was approved by the Senate a week ago, but was
approved again by the Senate later Thursday and sent to President
Reagan for his signature. The new Senate vote was necessitated by a
minor change made by the House.
</TEXT>
