<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Collision-Survivors     10-22 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Collision-Survivors,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher, Child Reported Missing After Ship Sinks. Children Return
Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ship Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of British children rescued after a ship
collision off Greece returned home Saturday for tearful reunions
with their families but the trip organizer said one child and a
teacher were missing.
   The missing child, 14-year-old Vivien Barley of Sutton Confield,
England, was presumed dead, according to Greece's Marine Ministry.
It had been reported she was the only one of the 486 students and
teachers in the group not found.
   However, the organizer of the trip, Schools Abroad, announced
Saturday evening that teacher Bernard Butt from T.P. Riley
Community College in Walsall, central England, was also missing.
   ``All we know is several (pupils) say he helped them out of the
boat following the accident and was last seen by them helping
children out of the boat, as is typical,'' said school headmaster
Martin Taylor. ``Since then, there is simply no information, and
obviously we are very, very concerned,'' he said in an interview on
Independent Television News.
   However, a spokeswoman for Epirotiki Lines, owners of the Greek
cruise ship Jupiter that carried the British travelers, said later,
on condition of anonymity: ``I know this man is alive and well. I
have spoken to him myself.''
   ``He was accounted for earlier today; now he is not,'' a British
Foreign Office spokesman said, also on condition of anonymity. ``He
certainly did not board any of the planes to Britain.''
   An Italian freighter collided Friday with the Greek cruise ship
carrying the British children and teachers off the Greek port city
of Piraeus. Two Greek seamen aboard the Jupiter were killed, and 54
passengers were injured. The cruise ship sank.
   Greek authorities detained the captain of the Italian freighter
Adige and accused him of being responsible for the accident.
   The rescued children flew home aboard four chartered Boeing 737
jets to Stansted, Gatwick and Manchester airports and rushed into
the arms of their parents. Some of the injured passengers remained
behind in Greek hospitals.
   Some youngsters _ rumpled, pale and still wrapped in blankets _
burst into tears at the sight of their families. One father
collapsed at Manchester Airport as he waited for his daughter to
arrive. He was taken to a hospital.
   Some children were unable to speak, but others poured out their
stories.
   Teacher Roy Embrey described the children as ``magnificent,
absolutely fantastic. If it had been adults, I do not think we
would have got as many off the ship as we did.
   ``Some of the children could not swim and others were afraid to
jump .... Once we were in the water, all we could do was to swim
like the devil.''
   Andrew Gillon, 19, said he escaped from the sinking ship as it
tilted almost vertically in the sea.
   ``It went up on one side, stood up, and then I realized we just
had to get off,'' he said. ``But there was one girl, Sara Korb, who
would not come with me. She would not let go so I tried to talk her
down.
   ``She would not let go of the ladder, so in the end I had to
pull her hands off.''
   His tearful mother, Margaret Gillon, clung to her son as he told
his tale. ``Until I heard he was safe, I couldn't cry,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
