<DOCNO> AP881022-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 1920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SonsKilled     10-22 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sons Killed,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Charged With Slashing Two Young Sons Throats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Puffe Sr., separated from his
wife, wanted to be with his two little boys.
   Now, he sits in an isolated jail cell with a wound healing on
his neck.
   He slashed his throat and lived. Police say he slashed the
throats of Timmy, 3, and Tommy, 2. They were buried Saturday.
   The 29-year-old father was charged last week with two counts of
first-degree murder, but a judge granted him permission Thursday to
see the boys one final time before their funerals.
   Puffe and his 27-year-old wife, Victoria, were getting a divorce
and custody of the boys was going to be a major issue. She and the
children had moved out in August and a temporary court order let
Puffe have the children on Sundays.
   Puffe was being held in lieu of $500,000 cash bail in a cell
equipped with a television monitor where officers ``are watching
him a bit more closely'' than other inmates, said Chief Deputy
Robert Andraschko of the Waupaca County Sheriff's Department.
   ``Timothy and Thomas will not have died in vain if we would see
children as a gift from God and not pawns in the lives and desires
of adults,'' the Rev. Donald Gauerke told about 100 mourners
Saturday at Trinity Lutheran Church.
   The church pastor urged family and friends to reflect on the
``joy and unending enthusiasm and vitality'' of the boys and to
forgive their father.
   The killings Oct. 15 left people stunned in the neighborhood of
neat lawns, no fences and well-kept, ranch-style homes. Basketball
hoops, bicycles and swing sets adorn many yards in this community
of about 6,200 about 40 miles southwest of Green Bay.
   ``Everybody has kids. It's just a neighborhood full of kids,''
said next-door neighbor Ellen Bodah. ``You can tell it kind of
bothers the kids.''
   The boys' mother and police found them in the house after Mrs.
Puffe received a phone call from her estranged husband. Mrs.
Puffe's daughter from a previous marriage, sleeping in another
bedroom, was unharmed.
   In a letter police found addressed to Mrs. Puffe, the father
wondered what his wife would joke about, ``now that I'm gone and I
took my little men with me,'' according to a criminal complaint.
   Neighbors and relatives described Puffe as a devoted father who
often worked 70 hours a week as a farmhand but spent every spare
moment with his sons.
   In a signed statement to police, Puffe said he drank about a
fourth of a quart of rum and wrote a note to his wife after putting
the children to bed.
   He took a knife from a kitchen drawer and lay down on the bed
where the two boys were, according to the statement filed in
circuit court.
   ``I cut Timmy first across the neck, I cut Tommy across the neck
right away, across the neck both the same way,'' the statement said.
   He called his wife and told her, ``I just killed the boys,''
then returned to the bedroom and lay between his sons, according to
the statement.
   ``With my right hand (I) cut my own throat,'' the statement
said. ``I wanted to be with my boys.''
   Police spoke twice with Puffe by telephone and he told them
there was no problem in the house. A third call went unanswered and
an officer looking through windows saw a man's figure lay down on a
bed, sit back up, fall sideways and crawl down a hall. Puffe
crawled out the front door of the home.
   He was hospitalized for a day and then went to jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
