<HEAD>Hussein, Mubarak, Arafat Meet to Seek Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th pvs ```It is...' to UPDATE with
Israeli reax, PICK up 6th pvs `A senior...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AQABA, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of Jordan, Egypt and the
Palestine Liberation Organization met Saturday in an effort to
forge common proposals for an international peace conference in the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Their summit was held with a view toward Israel's parliamentary
elections on Nov. 1 and a session of the Palestine National
Council, which acts as the PLO's parliament, on Nov. 12.
   ``This meeting aims at coordinating Arab positions so we can
move forward quickly to convening an international peace
conference,'' PLO chairman Yasser Arafat told reporters after
meeting with King Hussein of Jordan and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.
   ``We want the Israeli voter ... to determine his interests
before the November election,'' said Osama Baz, Mubarak's chief
political adviser, when asked about the summit's significance.
   ``It is important for him (the Israeli voter) to know that there
is an Arab partner who is ready for peace,'' Baz told reporters.
``If he does not want it, we will have something else to say.''
   In Israel, Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir of the rightist Likud bloc, denounced the Aqaba conference,
calling it an attempt to influence the Israeli election.
   But a spokesman for Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, the head of
Israel's socialist Labor Party, said the summit proved Peres'
proposal for peace talks between Israel and a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation is still viable.
   A senior PLO official in Aqaba, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the talks focused on the form of a proposed
confederation between Jordan and a Palestinian state and on
improving relations between Jordan and the PLO.
   In July, Hussein renounced Jordan's claims to the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and curtailed his nation's longstanding
administrative ties with the occupied territories. He previously
terminated joint efforts with the PLO to arrange peace talks with
Israel.
   Arafat last visited Jordan for an Arab summit in November 1987.
   He told reporters he still supports the PLO's commitment to a
confederation between Jordan and an independent Palestinian state.
   He said he would give the 450-member Palestine National Council
four options: Declaring a Palestinian state under occupation, a
provisional state and government, a provisional government alone,
or asking temporary international protection for the occupied
territories.
   Aides said Arafat and Mubarak planned to leave Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
