<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugBill 1stLd-Writethru a0633 10-22 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sweeping Anti-Drug Bill Toughens Penalties for Drug Dealing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update with Moynihan on bill signing, inserts new graf 6:
Sen. Daniel ....</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is expected to sign a broad
ranging anti-drug bill that calls for stiff penalties for drug
dealers including the death sentence in some cases involving
drug-related murders.
   The bill, characterized by Sen. Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., as ``bad news for drug dealers and their customers,'' was
approved by Congress early Saturday.
   ``This is a very strong bill. The message is simple. Don't do
drugs. The country will not tolerate it,'' declared Senate Majority
Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   The bill calls for creation of a Cabinet-level ``drug czar''
that would coordinate all aspects of the federal government's war
against illegal drugs. It also calls for stiffer penalties and a
variety of other sanctions, including loss of some federal benefits
and civil fines, for drug violations.
   White House spokeswoman Liz Murphy said she did not know when
the president will sign the legislation, adding that the bill had
not yet been sent over to the White House.
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., one of the principle
sponsors of the legislation, said Saturday he expects Reagan to
sign the bill swiftly.
   Congress worked late into the night to enact the legislation
that many congressmen and senators wanted in time for the final
days of their re-election campaigns.
   A dispute over proposed anti-obscenity language _ sought by
conservatives, but labeled unconstitutional by many liberals and
moderates _ held up the vote until the early morning hours Saturday.
   The matter was worked out when it was agreed to create a new
obscenity trafficking offense and the House went on to approve the
overall legislation on a 346-11 vote. Two hours later the Senate
passed the measure with a voice vote.
   The bill would allow up to a $10,000 civil fine for possession
of even small quantities of drugs intended for personal use and
could, beginning in September, lead to the loss of student loans
and other federal benefits for anyone convicted of drug possession.
   Drug kingpins and others who kill or order killings while
committing drug-related felonies could be executed under a federal
death penalty provision in the legislation.
   Other provisions of the bill would:
   _Require for the first time health warning labels on alcoholic
beverages.
   _Toughen child pornography laws, including creation of penalties
for anyone who aids in the use of a child for producing sexually
explicit materials.
   _Establishes a one-year pilot program for drug testing of new
drivers' license applicants.
   _Expands the government's role in drug treatment, prevention and
research programs.
   _Allows the president to impose sanctions against countries
involved in laundering drug money.
   Because of continuing disagreements among some legislators,
provisions that would have required random drug testing for
transportation workers and those with safety-related jobs at
nuclear facilities were left out of the legislation.
   In Atlanta, Micky Sadoff, president of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving, called the legislation ``a fantastic success'' because of
its provisions involving alcohol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
