<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Papandreou     10-22 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Papandreou,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Welcome Premier On His Return From Heart Surgery In
London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Greeks shouting ``Andreas
we're with you!'' gave Premier Andreas Papandreou a tumultuous
welcome when he arrived at Athens Airport after being in London for
two-months because of heart surgery.
   Waving banners in the green and white colors of Papandreou's
socialist party, the crowd pushed past police and surged around the
premier's plane.
   The 69-year-old Papandreou came slowly down the steps followed
by his friend Dimitra Liani, a former airline stewardess the
premier is expected to marry.
   Papandreou said in London he plans to divorce his U.S.-born wife
Margaret, who he married in 1951. Ms Liani, 34, is divorcing
architect Alex Kapopoulos, 45.
   Speaking with reporters aboard the plane, Papandreou said he
would stay active in politics. ``With all my strength, my knowledge
and my mental and physical capacity I will continue to serve the
interests of our people,'' he said.
   Papandreou came to power in 1981 and won a second four-year term
in 1985.
   There has been some question if he would campaign actively at
the head of his Panhellenic Socialist Movement in national
elections due by June 1989.
   Papandreou underwent open-heart surgery Sept. 30 at Harefield
Hospital in London.
   He did not name a replacement during his illness and continued
to supervise the government by telephone from the hospital. Cabinet
ministers frequently flew to London to confer with him.
</TEXT>
