<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TrialandError 2ndLd-Writethru a0635 10-22 1107</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trial and Error, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0635,1040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It Was A Good Two Years, Or a Bad Two, Depending on Who You Speak
To</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Eight members ...'' to CORRECT
number to six.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-The 100th Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 535 men and women who made up the 100th
Congress had a very good two years or a very bad two years,
depending on your point of view.
   In the 100th Congress the Senate subways did not run on time and
senators missed votes, a shouting congressman had his mike turned
off, a senator was arrested and Oliver North stole the show at the
Iran-Contra hearings.
   In the House the telephones stopped working, nearly all of them.
   In the Senate, the telephones worked too well, picking up
conversations from other offices without the knowledge of those
doing the conversing.
   Six members of the 100th Congress ran for their party's
presidential nomination _ Reps. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Jack
Kemp, R-N.Y.; and Sens. Bob Dole, R-Kan., Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
Albert Gore, D-Tenn., and Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   None of them made it.
   But two members who did not make the run _ Sens. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, and Dan Quayle, R-Ind., found themselves on their party's
ticket anyway, as someone else's vice presidential running mate.
   Biden was later to contend that the furor over plagiarism that
forced him from the race saved his life.
   Saved his life?
   Biden spent months in the hospital recovering from operations
for a brain aneurysm that was diagnosed shortly after he ended his
candidacy.
   He said, and staff members agreed, that he would have ignored
the pain and plunged ahead with his campaign had he not been forced
from the race after disclosures he had adopted parts of the
speeches of other politicians word for word.
   That could have killed him, Biden said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   One senator was credited with saving another senator's life.
   Sen. John Kerry. D-Mass., came upon Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., in
a Senate hallway, choking. A slice of apple was stuck in his throat.
   Kerry, who had never before performed the Heimlich maneuver,
applied it four times, successfully dislodging the obstruction.
   ``He's a strong guy, he picked me right up and knew just what to
do,'' said Hecht.
   Any small irony in that?
   Well, yes.
   Kerry is chairman of the Democratic senatorial election
campaign, which is doing its best to upset Hecht's bid for
re-election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Throughout the 100th Congress, Democrats struggled to pass a
campaign spending limitations bill over Republican opposition.
   In the end they failed.
   But the battle will be remembered.
   At 1:30 a.m. one day last March, Republicans fled the Senate
floor to prevent a quorum from being established and to force the
Democratic leadership to adjourn.
   A call went out for the sergeant-at-arms to arrest absent
senators.
   Sergeant-at-Arms Henry Giugni used a master key to enter the
private office of Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore.
   Packwood was arrested and escorted to the Senate chamber.
   But he refused to enter.
   Giugni ordered a squad of detectives to lift Packwood from his
feet and to carry him inside.
   They did so and his presence gave the Democrats a quorum and the
Republicans a severe case of outrage.
   The Senate remained in session all night.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Senate worried about its ``quality of life.''
   Younger senators, especially those with children, grumbled about
legislative chaos, sessions that stretched deep into the night,
roll calls that stretched far beyond their allotted 15 minutes, a
``Tuesday-Thursday Club'' that saw senators stretch a two-day
weekend into four.
   Action was taken.
   In exchange for time off every fourth week, senators were
expected to be present Monday through Friday for the rest of the
month.
   Roll calls were restricted to 15 minutes with no waiting for
senators who did not show up on time.
   Almost immediately the law of unintended consequences went into
effect.
   With the 15-minute clock running, a band of senators piled off
elevators in the subway lobby of the Hart Senate Office building.
   The roofless, three-car train was waiting.
   But it was filled with visitors who happened to be blind.
   It took a while for the senators to get possession of the train.
   Fuming, they stormed onto the Senate floor minutes after the
roll call ended, only to be told that they could not vote and would
not be recorded.
   Now, during roll calls, the trains are reserved for the
exclusive transportation of senators.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Senate oratory can get heated, and at times just a little
twisted.
   As the 100th Congress neared its end, Sen. Steve Symms,
R-Idaho., complained at length about the failure of Congress to
provide further military aid to the Contras in Nicaragua.
   He said:
   ``The gutless no-good 100th Congress on this issue has decided
to create its own doctrine, and that is to write it off.
   ``In other words, we will write off freedom in Nicaragua, throw
them to the alligators and hope the alligators will eat someone
else and eat us last and they can peel off a slice of that salami
and they will not bother us for now. Do not rock the boat.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., made the last speech of his
31-year Senate career.
   He said the job of being a U.S. senator was the best job in the
world, better even than being president of the United States.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., rose to praise
both speech and senator.
   Both were, Byrd said, ``Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious.''
   That, he said, means ``good.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., also felt good.
   Ackerman used to weigh more than 280 pounds.
   He dieted. He exercised. And, in triumph, he went to the House
floor to announce he had lost more than 100 pounds.
   ``The House historian has confirmed that my weight loss is the
biggest of any member of Congress in history,'' the congressman
crowed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, presided over the congressional
Iran-Contra hearings wearing dark glasses to protect his eyes,
which were damaged by the glaring brightness of television lights
when he served as a member of the Senate Watergate Committee.
   But Inouye, who is of Japanese descent, said that the
Iran-Contra investigation was not the highlight of his year.
   The senator, who is also chairman of the Senate Indian affairs
subcommittee, was made an honorary Navajo at a sunrise ceremony on
a ridge in New Mexico and given a title: ``The Chief Who Returns
With a Plan.''
   ``I have a lot of plans,'' said Inouye, who, with his
colleague's consent, hopes to become majority leader in the 101st
Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
