<HEAD>Groups Organize Relief Efforts for Hurricane Stricken Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S.-based agenices announced Saturday they are sending
money, food and other supplies to Nicaragua and Costa Rica, which
have been devastated by the 125 mph winds and torrential rains of
Hurricane Joan.
   The death toll from the storm had reached 33 by Saturday, while
more than 77,000 people had been evacuated from their homes.
   Oxfam America of Boston hoped to get canned food, powdered milk,
beans, cooking oil, tents and roofing material to the storm-ravaged
areas within two days, said spokesman Phillip Martin.
   And Operation California, a Los Angeles-based charity group, has
scheduled an emergency airlift for Thursday aboard a Costa Rican
cargo plane, said organization President Richard Walden.
   Oxfam, which operates international development and relief
programs in 32 countries, including Nicaragua, plans to fly the
supplies from Mexico to Managua, Martin said.
   Operation California, founded in 1979 by Walden airlifted
$750,000 worth of medical and shelter aid to Jamaica, which was hit
by Hurricane Gilbert.
