<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Austad     10-22 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Austad,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador To Norway and Finland Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Evans Austad, former U.S. ambassador to
Norway and Finland, has died at age 71.
   Austad, who died Thursday of heart disease, was appointed U.S.
ambassador to Finland in 1974, and was the U.S. ambassador to
Norway from 1980 to 1984.
   The Norwegian government awarded him the Great Cross of St.
Olav, the highest civilian honor, for his help in fighting heart
disease. He raised large amounts of money for research and arranged
for American doctors to teach Norwegian doctors heart surgery
techniques.
   Austad began his career in broadcasting at station KSL in Salt
Lake City, and later succeeded Arthur Godfrey as the CBS Washington
commentator. He was a founding trust member of Metromedia, where he
was vice president from 1961 to 1981.
   He was vice chairman of the 1972 inauguration of President Nixon
and was a delegate to the United Nations General Assembly.
   He served on the boards of the National Association of
Broadcasters, The National Chamber of Commerce, the International
Heart Foundation, the Arizona Heart Institute Board and the
Disabled American Veterans.
   Austad is survived by his wife, Lola Brown, and three daughters.
</TEXT>
