<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Housing-Theft     10-22 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing-Theft,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Aide Says He Stole to Help Starving People in Ghana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former housing authority official who said
he was inspired to steal more than $120,000 to help starving
villagers in his native Ghana was sentenced to two years in jail
and ordered to pay back the money.
   U.S. District Judge Marvin Katz on Friday also sentenced Anthony
Andoh, 43, to five years' probation after the jail term and ordered
him to pay back $126,337 in public housing funds stolen from the
Philadelphia Housing Authority and the New Haven Housing Authority
in Connecticut.
   Andoh was the finance director for the Philadelphia agency in
1985 and 1986, and the finance director for the New Haven agency in
1984 and early 1985.
   He pleaded guilty in July to stealing $48,314 from the
Philadelphia agency and to embezzling $78,023 from the New Haven
agency, but said in court Friday that he was moved to do so by the
suffering in the African country of Ghana.
   ``What I saw in Ghana in 1980 when I visited was synonymous with
the Holocaust,'' Andoh said. ``People were dying by the thousands.
People were fleeing the country. Everyone was suffering. They were
struggling just to get something to eat.''
   Andoh said those images haunted him when he returned to the
United States and inspired him to steal.
   Investigators found no evidence of Andoh giving any of the money
to charity.
