<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 2300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PollTurmoil 1stLd-Writethru a0551 10-22 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poll Turmoil, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>As Election Nears, Pollsters Still See Uneasy Electorate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 13th graf pvs, bgng: ``An NBC-Journal
...'' to UPDATE with Newsweek poll.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls are illuminating an electorate in turmoil,
with voters still groping _ some of them dispiritedly _ toward a
decision in the presidential election, analysts say.
   While surveys indicate a healthy George Bush lead, striking
differences in gauging the size of the lead underline a certain
unhappiness with the choices, some pollsters said in recent days.
   And that means things still can change with just over two weeks
to go, they said.
   ``People are having lots of second thoughts,'' said Andrew
Kohut, president of the Gallup Organization. Even in polls that
have found stable results for weeks, he said, ``I term it stable
uncertainty.''
   Several pollsters _ but not all _ agreed with such an analysis:
That a good number of voters, even at this late date, remain
loosely committed to either Bush or to Democrat Michael Dukakis,
and could change their minds.
   ``I see more indecision than usual, and I ascribe that a lot to
the negativism of the campaign,'' said I.A. Lewis, chief of polling
for the Los Angeles Times. ``I think there's a kind of reluctance
for people to commit themselves to one of two people, neither of
whom they like.''
   Lewis, in the Times poll, has found that four in 10 of Dukakis'
supporters and nearly three in 10 of Bush's oppose the other
candidate more than they favor their own _ hardly an inspiring
reason to cast a vote.
   Gallup has found less than half of each candidate's supporters
backing him strongly, and a sizable share, roughly three in 10,
saying they could change their minds. And in an NBC News-Wall
Street Journal poll, 57 percent of likely voters wished they had a
different set of choices.
   ``Neither of these guys seems to attract the kind of commitment
that some other presidential candidates have had,'' said Larry
Hugick, political pollster for Gallup. Even though Gallup has found
a stable Bush lead since August, he said, ``If you look at the
depth of commitment, you'll see there's still potential for
change.''
   The view of a still-volatile electorate was not unanimous. Jeff
Alderman, pollster for ABC News, saw a more stable contest. His
surveys, like Gallup's bi-weekly ones, have found a steady lead for
Bush, and he has found considerably stronger support for the
candidates than Gallup has.
   ``My polling doesn't show very much volatility at all,'' said
Alderman, who has polled every night since Labor Day. ``There's a
clear indication of a very stable race.''
   But not all polls are in line with each other.
   An NBC-Journal poll, taken Friday through Sunday last weekend,
found an enormous 17-point Bush lead. A Harris poll Friday to
Monday the same weekend put it down to nine points. And an
ABC-Washington Post poll from the previous Wednesday to Tuesday put
it at seven, roughly where it's been for weeks.
   Most recently, a Newsweek poll of 1,013 registered voters
conducted by telephone on Thursday and Friday showed Bush leading
Dukakis 50 percent to 41 percent, with a margin of error of 4
percentage points.
   NBC pollster Laurily Epstein said her poll could have caught a
swing to Bush after the presidential debate last week, then missed
some shifting back to Dukakis on Monday. She noted that Bush
received wide publicity as the debate winner.
   Other pollsters shared her view, noting that Dukakis surged
after the Democratic convention last summer and Bush after the
Republican convention, but settled back as the publicity wore off.
   Their hypothesis: When voters don't have strong opinions, they
are more likely to be influenced by events, albeit momentarily.
   ``Polling immediately after momentous events catches people in
the process of making up their minds. What you see are these
distortions,'' said Kohut, the Gallup president. He likened it to a
runner's pulse after a race: ``It's an accurate reading. But you
can't generalize a lot from it.''
   Kohut and others said such skittishness in the electorate
magnifies the methodological differences in polls _ whether or not
they urge undecided voters to make a choice, for example _ and can
help skew results.
</TEXT>
