<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Time     10-22 0104</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Time,0106</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Back To GMT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Sunday reverted from Summer Time to
Greenwich Mean Time, moving clocks back one hour at 2 a.m. to 1
a.m. Ireland did the same.
   The traditional change again put Britain out of step with most
of Western Europe, which is one hour ahead of GMT in winter and two
hours ahead in summer.
   Summer Time, lasting from March to October, was first introduced
in 1916 to provide an extra evening hour of light for farmers and
save electricity during World War I. But it also means mornings are
darker for an hour.
</TEXT>
