<HEAD>New York, Chicago Papers Endorse Bush, Atlanta, St. Louis Papers
Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with six graphs to include endorsements by New York, St.
Louis and Cleveland papers; picks up 4th graf pvs: Dukakis also
....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush picked up editorial
endorsements Saturday from newspapers in Chicago, New York and
Cleveland while Democrat Michael Dukakis won endorsements from
papers in Atlanta, St. Louis and Dayton, Ohio.
   The Chicago Tribune and the Chicago Sun-Times each endorsed Bush
in their Sunday editions, though the Tribune lamented the quality
of the campaign and Bush's choice of Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., as a
running mate.
   Also endorsing Bush in their Sunday editions were the New York
Daily News, which said there are more fitting candidates than he or
Dukakis but that ``none will be on the ballot,'' and the Plain
Dealer of Cleveland.
   ``In a time of peace and prosperity, even a prosperity built on
credit, most voters don't want to take a chance,'' the Plain Dealer
said, adding that voters know more about Bush than Dukakis.
   The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution said in their
joint Sunday editions Dukakis would ``strike the newer course of
the two'' candidates and ``... has shown a far better grasp of the
nation and its people.''
   The St. Louis Post-Dispatch said in its Sunday editions that
Dukakis ``has been more realistic'' than Bush in addressing the
trade and federal budget deficits and ``has set forth a humane and
enlightened social policy.''
   Dukakis also picked up an endorsement from the Dayton Daily News
in Ohio, which said in its Sunday editions that he ``has a keener
intellect than George Bush.''
   The Chicago Tribune called Bush's campaign ``abysmal'' but said
it favors him over Dukakis because ``we agree more with what he
says and fear less his leadership in the White House.''
   The Sun-Times said Bush was its ``emphatic choice'' for
president and called the Republican ``probably the most experienced
candidate ever to run for president.''
