<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0618 10-22 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0618,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Tries to Revive Southern Chances</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5 grafs for grafs 3-4 pvs, bgng: ``At sunup ...'' to
UPDATE with appearance before Italian group. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
bgng: ``Before some ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BEAUMONT, Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAWKINSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis defended his
record on crime Saturday in the South, where his prospects have
been hurt by George Bush's allegations on the subject.
   Later, in a taped speech on ABC-TV, the Democratic presidential
candidate accused Bush of waging a campaign ``of fear and of
smear.''
   At sunup Saturday, Dukakis spoke at a crowded pipefitters union
hall in Beaumont, accompanied by his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen. He capped the day by speaking back-to-back with Bush
before the National Italian American Foundation in Washington.
   ``Many of you know the vice president's been going to a lot of
ethnic festivals lately,'' Dukakis told the Italian group.
``George, it would have saved you a lot of time if you'd just
picked Pete Domenici to be your running mate.'' Domenici, a
Republican senator from New Mexico, is the son of Italian
immigrants.
   Dukakis, who delivered part of his address in Italian, repeated
many of the same self-deprecating jokes that he delivered at the Al
Smith dinner in New York two days earlier.
   On a serious note, he told the group: ``The immigrants' dream is
the American dream. It is now in our hands. We must never forget
that dream belongs not just to the privileged few but to all of
us.''
   Earlier, Dukakis visited Hawkinsville, Ga., for a barbecue rally
with top Georgia Democrats in what was to be a show of solidarity
in a major Southern state where the campaign has been in trouble.
   Before some 4,000 people at a rally in a high school football
field in rural Georgia, Dukakis was joined by former President
Jimmy Carter and the state's top elected Democrats.
   ``People say there's not a very good chance that we'll have a
governor from Massachusetts in the White House,'' Carter said.
``But I think that we and you and Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen
can turn it around.''
   Sen. Sam Nunn denounced Bush's campaign as one of ``distortions
and in many cases outright and total lies.''
   Attacking Bush's use of the case of furloughed inmate Willie
Horton, who attacked a family while released from a Massachusetts
prison, Nunn described in graphic detail the rape and murder of a
pregnant young mother by an inmate furloughed from a federal prison
under President Reagan _ and said it was Richard Nixon who signed
into law the federal furlough program.
   ``A governor and a president cannot prevent all the horrible
crimes we have today, even though it's on his watch,'' Nunn said.
``A presidential candidate, though, can be expected to tell the
truth and put it in perspective. And Vice President Bush has a duty
to do that.''
   The case of Patsy Pedrin is one Dukakis is usuing in new
television ads and which he spoke about earlier Texas and Louisiana
_ while saying he would ``never use that kind of human tragedy''
for political purposes.
   In both Texas and Georgia, where he campaigned Saturday, and in
Louisiana where he was Friday night, Dukakis trails Bush in polls
by as much as 10 points.
   In his Texas speech, Dukakis recounted the crimes of a prisoner
released on furlough from a federal prison while Bush was vice
president.
   ``I would never use that kind of human tragedy to accuse the
president of being soft on crime,'' Dukakis said. ``Maybe that's
the difference beteen me and George Bush.''
   In his television speech, which was set for 10:55 p.m. EDT on
ABC, Dukakis spoke of the beating and robbing of his father and the
hit-and-run death of his brother as examples of how ``my family has
been touched by violence.''
   ``I've led the fight against crime and drugs in my own state and
I intend to do so as president,'' he said.
   Before the rally with state party leaders in Georgia, state
Democratic chairman John Henry Anderson said, ``With this kind of
show of support, it sends a signal to the people of this state that
we're comfortable with our nominee.''
</TEXT>
