<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Interior-Jobs     10-22 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interior-Jobs,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Proposes Cutting 2,000 Positions from Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel has proposed
cutting 2,000 jobs in his 69,000-employee department, starting a
year from now, according to a report in The New York Times' Sunday
editions.
   An internal memorandum disclosed that Hodel proposed turning
many of those jobs over to private contractors, according to the
newspaper, which said it obtained the memo from sources outside the
government.
   More than 500 of the proposed cuts would be made in the National
Park Service, the Times said. The proposal calls for a study of the
feasibility of turning over to the private sector such jobs as
orientation services for park visitors and park maintenance.
   The proposal also suggests turning the map-making function of
the U.S. Geological Survey over to private enterprise, the Times
said.
   The memo was written by Richard Ventura, the assistant interior
secretary for policy, budget and administration.
   A department spokesman, Alan Levitt, said a second memorandum
stressed that no employees would be forced to retire. He said
normal attrition in the department was higher than the number of
proposed cuts.
</TEXT>
