<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 2334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-SeriesProtest     10-22 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Series Protest,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Angry over `Sleazy, Cheap' TV Drama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS support organization Saturday
called an NBC-TV series sleazy for an episode depicting the
fictitious murder of a bisexual man who knowingly infects sexual
partners with the deadly virus.
   ``NBC should not exploit the human tragedy of the AIDS epidemic
to increase rating points and profits,'' said Timothy Wolfred,
executive director of the San Francisco AIDS Foundation.
   Fearing the episode would unleash violence against carriers of
the virus, 60 demonstrators earlier this week shut down the
shooting on an outdoor scene of ``Midnight Caller,'' an action
drama series set in San Francisco. The first episode is scheduled
to air Tuesday night.
   The protests, set to resume Monday when Lorimar productions
resumes shooting, began after negotiations between several AIDS
groups, the show's producers, NBC officials and representatives of
the mayor's office failed to reach an agreement on changes in the
script.
   ``We are not asking NBC and the producers to cancel a `Midnight
Caller' episode on AIDS,'' Wolfred said in a statement Saturday.
``We would wholeheartedly support an episode that promotes
understanding of HIV disease.''
   A handout distributed with the statement called the disputed
episode, which will be shown sometime in the future, ``sleazy ...
sensational .... cheap television drama.''
   NBC said it has agreed to talk more with demonstrators next week
but insisted shooting will resume on Monday.
   In the episode in question, a bisexual man carrying the AIDS
virus purposely infects others by having sexual relations with
them. One of the partners, a woman who discovers she carries the
AIDS virus, shoots and kills the man at the end of the episode.
   Bob Singer, executive producer of the program, said he decided
to leave the murder in the script but that he asked for revisions
to reflect demonstrators' concerns.
   ``The hero says that the murder is absolutely the wrong
solution,'' said Singer. ``No one watching it could think we were
condoning this by any stretch of the imagination.''
</TEXT>
