<HEAD>Bush Says He Doesn't Approve Illinois GOP Anti-Dukakis Brochures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Bush-Dukakis nite appearance at banquet,
inserts new grafs 5-10, bgng: At a ....; picks up 7th graf pvs: On
another ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Saturday he
does not approve of campaign literature that Republicans in
Illinois distributed saying Democrat Michael Dukakis is supported
by rapists, murderers and other criminals.
   ``No I don't and I don't back some of the stuff they're saying
about me. ... No I disapprove of that,'' Bush said, without
elaborating on what in particular he was taking exception to on the
Democratic side.
   He made the statement in answer to a question following a
meeting Saturday with former Cuban political prisoner Armando
Valladares, who was freed after 22 years in 1982.
   Bush called the Cuban, who wrote the book ``Against All Hope,''
an ``inspiration to all who are for human rights.''
   At a banquet Saturday night sponsored by the National Italian
American Foundation, Bush and Dukakis shared a dais for the second
time in three days.
   They shook hands briefly and both applauded politely as the
other was introduced. Before the dinner, Bush met briefly with
former Italian Prime Minister Bettino Craxi.
   In brief remarks, the vice president recalled his emotions when
he has witnessed immigrants take the oath of U.S. citizenship.
   ``I saw their tears of joy and felt their appreciation of the
American dream,'' Bush told the crowd of 3,000 attending the
dinner. ``We share that joy tonight ... and we resolve together as
Americans to preserve and protect and, indeed, extend it in the
years ahead.''
   Bush's campaign also announced the formation of Catholics for
Bush-Quayle '88, to be headed by former GOP Cabinet members William
Simon and William Bennett, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and
conservative activist Phyllis Schlafly.
   In general, the vice president was spending a quiet weekend
mostly out of the campaign spotlight. He planned to head to New
England on Monday, then begin an extended campaign trip across the
country.
   On another matter raised by questioners outside his residence
Saturday, Bush responded briefly when asked for a comment on the
racketeering indictment of former Philippine President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   ``That speaks for itself, and let the justice system go forward;
that's what I say,'' said Bush.
   The indictment returned Friday in New York alleges Marcos and
his wife Imelda defrauded three U.S. lending institutions of $165
million in order to buy and finance real estate in New York, and
amassed $103 million through embezzlement, bribes and kickbacks
then laundered the money through secret bank accounts.
   Bush said little about the presidential campaign except in
answer to a question about the Illinois brochures.
   Distributed by the state party, they bore the headline, ``All
the Murderers and Rapists and Drug Pushers and Child Molesters in
Masschusetts Vote For Michael Dukakis.''
   Bush has consistently sought to portray Dukakis as soft on
crime, citing in particular Massachusetts' former prisoner-furlough
program.
   Dukakis held up the Illinois brochures in campaign appearances
Wednesday and called them ``political garbage.''
</TEXT>
