<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-OilFraud     10-22 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Oil Fraud,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oilworkers' Union Accuses Governor Of Fraud; Investigation
Launched</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chamber of Deputies is investigating
charges by the oilworkers union that the governor of Mexico state
embezzled $49 million from the government petroleum monopoly Pemex
when he headed it.
   Seven deputies from the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, made the accusation against Gov. Mario Ramon Beteta
Thursday night.
   As PRI deputy Adolfo Barrientos, head of a local union, spoke,
oilworkers crowded into the chamber's public galleries shouted:
``To the gallows, to jail'' and ``He robbed the nation,'' the
financial daily El Financiero said.
   The speaker of the chamber named a 22-member commission to
investigate the charges. The investigation was approved by deputies
from both the PRI majority and opposition parties.
   Beteta, an economist and former treasury secretary, left Pemex
in January when he his took office as governor of the state of
Mexico.
   He was named head of Pemex by President Miguel de la Madrid as
part of his ``moral renewal'' campaign against corruption. He
replaced Jorge Diaz Serrano, whose conviction for embezzling $58.7
million from Pemex in a 1980 oil tanker deal was a showcase of the
campaign.
   During his five years as Pemex chief, Beteta clashed repeatedly
with the union.
   Barrientos accused Beteta of defrauding Pemex of $49 million
through a 1985 deal for two Yugoslav-built tankers, and said the
union had documents to back up its allegations.
   He said the deal involved a company called Flota Petrolera
Mexicana, which bought a pair of Yugoslav-built tankers with only
$2.5 million in capital, then leased them to Pemex for a profit of
$49 million.
   Barrientos also accused the former commercial director of Pemex,
Donasiano Tamez; a PRI senator from the state of Mexico, Jesus
Alcantara Miranda; and the president of Flota Petrolera Mexicana,
Isidoro Rodriguez, of being involved in the deal.
</TEXT>
