<HEAD>NEW YORK: ... judgment was.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other business news this past week:
   _Furniture and apparel maker Interco Inc. rejected a sweetened
$2.7 billion tender offer from an investment group and boosted the
value of the company's own restructuring plan.
   _The board of GAF Corp. accepted a $1.47 billion buyout from a
group led by Chairman Samuel J. Heyman capping a 13-month-long
effort.
   _Ramada Inc., intent on focusing on its profitable gambling
operations, unveiled a restructuring plan that includes selling off
its hotel and restaurant businesses and distributing at least $278
million to shareholders.
   _Tyson Foods Inc. began a sweetened $941.2 million tender offer
for its rival poultry processor, Holly Farms Corp.
   _California's Supreme Court ruled that the state's attorney
general could not use the state's antitrust law to challenge the
federally approved $10.1 billion buyout of Getty Oil Co. by Texaco
Inc.
   _Time Inc. agreed to pay an initial $185 million for
half-interest in Whittle Communications LP, a fast-growing media
company.
   _Financier Carl C. Icahn met with leaders of ailing Eastern
Airlines' unions about a joint takeover of the airline but
abandoned the talks.
   _Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., accused by the Securities and
Exchange Commission of extensive fraud, disclosed that federal
prosecutors have formally notifiedthe Wall Street firm it is the
target of a grand jury investigation. A federal appeals court
halted proceedings in the civil case against Drexel so it could
consider arguments that the presiding judge should disqualify
himself.
   _A state judge ruled that H. Ross Perot cannot enter any
profitable deals that compete with Electronic Data Systems, his old
company.
   _The Pentagon suspended Sundstrand Corp. from doing business
with the government, saying it wasn't satisfied with the company's
response to being caught up in a huge defense fraud case.
   _American Telephone & Telegraph Co., which reported a 16.2
percent increase in quarterly profits, said it plans to cut its
basic interstate long-distance rates by an average of 3.8 percent
and prices for some business services by up to 6.2 percent on Dec.
1.
   _The government said higher food costs brought on by the drought
boosted retail prices a modest 0.3 percent last month. Nearly
balancing the steeper grocery prices was the sharpest drop in
gasoline costs since February. Other reports showed slight
increases in business inventories and housing construction and a
mild slowdown in factory use.
   _The Agriculture Department said that despite drought, the net
cash income of farmers in 1988 is expected to nearly match or
exceed last year's record $57.1 billion.
   _On the anniversary of last October's stock market crash,
federal regulators announced approval of a plan for coordinated
trading halts _ or circuit breakers _ in stock and futures markets
during steep price dives.
   _Japan marked the anniversary of the crash with the ultimate
vote of confidence _ the largest equity issue in the world so far
this year. The release of new shares in Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone Corp., the world's biggest company, started successfully
despite the hefty price of nearly $15,000 per share.
   _Maurice Allais, a prolific theorist whose ideas on balancing
supply and demand helped rebuild the French economy after World War
II, won the Nobel Prize for economics.
</TEXT>
