<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct 22-23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Sees Benefit, and Danger, in Buyout Binge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT header coding.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The takeover-buyout mania now sweeping through
corporate America has some Wall Streeters applauding and others
shaking their heads.
   The fans of these multibillion-dollar deals say they are
powerful medicine for a stock market still struggling to recover
from the crash of 1987.
   In the absence of buying by individuals and many institutional
money managers, they ask, where would the stock market be today
without the leveraged-buyout specialists and the traders, known as
arbitragers, who follow in their wake?
   What's more, they say, takeovers and buyouts are a long-term
plus for the market because they reduce the supply of stock in the
marketplace, giving an upward bias to the prices of the shares that
remain available.
   But more skeptical observers, while acknowledging some of those
points, argue that all this wheeling and dealing is contributing
huge new amounts to an already dangerous accumulation of debt in
the U.S. economy.
   And the activity it generates in the market, they say,
represents unhealthy speculation rather than stable, long-term
investment.
   The mergers and acquisitions binge is nothing new, of course.
Takeovers and buyouts were a dominant force in the 1982-87 bull
market.
   A similar phenomenon occurred in the 1960s, when
conglomerate-building was the financial rage.
   Lately, however, the game has been played on an expanded scale.
In the past week alone, Philip Morris proposed an $11.4 billion
offer for Kraft and RJR Nabsico said it was considering a $17.6
billion management buyout plan.
   If such deals can be done, analysts say, there appears to be
virtually no limit to what might be attempted in the future, no
company too big to be ruled out as a takeover or buyout candidate.
   That prospect helped propel stock prices higher in the past
week. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 50.32 to
2,183.50, hitting its highest levels since the crash of '87 as the
first anniversary of that debacle passed.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index gained 3.96 to
159.42; the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
added 4.00 to 388.59, and the American Stock Exchange market value
index was up 3.52 at 306.07.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 170.63 million shares a day, up
from 147.05 million the week before.
   ``The short-term rewards to selling shareholders in the form of
capital gains are indisputable,'' analysts at Wright Investors'
Service in Bridgeport, Conn., observed in a recent appraisal of the
mergers-and-acquisitions craze.
   But ``the longer-term effects of takeovers are less healthy for
the economy and for equity investors generally.''
   Excessive debt-leveraging of corporate assets makes companies
more vulnerable in the event of a recession, the report said.
   ``In fact, there is the potential that defaults arising from
high debt service requirements for companies with reduced cash
flows will even aggravate the economy's troubles, when the next
recession comes.
   ``Although industry consolidations and restructurings may often
be useful for strengthening the competitive edge in global markets,
the transformation of billions of dollars of equity into debt is
eroding the financial footings of U.S. industry.
   ``Market volatility and instability have increased as a result
of the takeover wave, with the effect of driving many individual
investors out of the stock market for years to come, if not for
good,'' it said.
   Wright noted that the greatest takeover wave in history was a
basic cause of the stock market decline last October. The collapse
was as severe as it was ``precisely because the takeover wave had
pushed stock prices to artificially high levels,'' the report said.
   ``For that reason alone,'' Wright concluded, ``one should find
little comfort in the continuing high level of takeover activity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
