<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Control Of Futures Markets Remains Unresolved Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
commodity price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after Black Monday, the question of which government
agency should oversee the financial futures markets remains
unresolved, a fact highlighted this past week at a gathering of
futures industry leaders and regulators in Chicago.
   A number of other crash-related issues also overhang the
nation's futures and options exchanges, but none arouses a more
emotional response among futures industry leaders than the control
question, especially among officials of the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and the Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest
futures exchanges.
   Futures and options trading is regulated by the 14-year-old
Commodities and Futures Trading Commission. Trading of stocks and
bonds is regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission, set
up in 1934 as part of the New Deal.
   Despite the undeniable link between the stock market and
stock-index futures _ which can be used for either hedging stock
positions or speculating on stock-market movements _ the Chicago
exchanges have strongly opposed post-crash proposals that one
agency should regulate both markets.
   Instead, they have argued for the creation of an agency that
would coordinate sharing of trading information among all the
financial markets.
   SEC Chairman David Ruder asked Congress in January to enlarge
his agency's jurisdiction to give it ``direct regulatory
authority'' over stock-index futures and any new futures contracts
related to stocks.
   In Chicago on Thursday, Ruder took a more lenient stance, saying
post-crash efforts to better coordinate the activities of the SEC,
the CFTC and the markets were working satisfactorily.
   ``Nonetheless,'' Ruder said in a speech to the Economic Club of
Chicago, ``I continue to believe that in the long term there needs
to be an ability to look beyond the parochial concerns of each of
the separate stock and futures markets. In the long run, unified
jurisdiction over these increasingly linked and unified markets
will prove to be desirable.''
   Earlier in the day, while sitting on a discussion panel with
CFTC Chairwoman Wendy Gramm and four futures industry leaders,
Ruder was even more conciliatory on the issue, saying that
``contrary to many press reports, I do not regard that as a very
serious matter.''
   Chicago Merc President William Brodsky, who also sat on the
panel, expressed his position bluntly: ``I don't think you need a
single regulator to create cooperation.''
   Ms. Gramm, a Reagan appointee who has been in office less than
eight months, did not comment on the control issue but focused
instead on the likelihood of increased regulation of futures
trading under a Michael Dukakis administration.
   Dukakis is a Democrat and most of the bills introduced in
Congress in the past year proposing greater regulation of the
futures markets were sponsored by Democrats.
   But Ms. Gramm said she expected Republican Vice President George
Bush to win the November election. The big question, she said, was
whether Bush would be willing to veto any futures-related
legislation backed by a Congress likely to be dominated by
Democrats.
   The issue of regulatory jurisdiction over financial futures
could come to a head next year when Congress must vote on
reauthorizing the CFTC for another four years. By law, the agency
dies next year unless reauthorized by Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881022-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-22-88 0218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RefineryCutbacks     10-22 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refinery Cutbacks,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron USA Plans 400 Fewer Jobs at Port Arthur Refinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron USA, citing increased
competition and reduced profit, announced plans Friday to cut the
workforce at its largest refinery by about 400 jobs.
   Company officials said a portion of the jobs will be eliminated
through attrition and early retirement.
   The 4,000-acre plant was purchased by the Chevron subsidiary in
1984 from Gulf Oil Corp, and employs more than 2,200 people.
   ``Chevron USA has announced plans to streamline the refinery
operations and the organization here to make the refinery more
competitive _ and not only to make it more competitive, but to
assure its continued operation,'' said company spokesman Art
Spencer.
   The exact number of layoffs will not be known until company
officials meet with union leaders to discuss the changes, he said,
but Chevron plans to operate the plant with about 400 fewer
employees.
   ``Any announcement involving a reduction in manpower is
difficult, but this has come as something of a relief to many of
our Port Arthur business people because it means that Chevron has
decided to keep the plant open,'' Spencer said.
   A company task force had presented four options to improve
refining operation profits, including the possibility of shutting
down the plant, or reducing the workforce by more than half,
Spencer sasid.
   ``This was the best of the (task force) alternatives,'' he said.
``It's a relief that we did not have to go to the big numbers.''
   The changes were prompted, in part, by continuing volatility in
the energy industry, he said.
   ``It relates to the extremely competitive market in which this
refinery functions,'' Spencer said.
   ``This Gulf Coast region is the most competitive petroleum
products market in the United States,'' he said. ``We have not been
competitive in this market for a long time.''
   Smaller Chevron refining operations in Pascagoula, Miss., and El
Paso have proven more profitable, he said.
   The Port Arthur refinery is the largest owned by Chevron, with
an operating capacity off 407,000 barrels of crude per day. After
streamlining, which is expected to begin immediately, ready
capacity will be about 329,000 barrels per day, Spencer said.
   ``We've never run 400,000 barrels a day here,'' he said.
   A renewed marketing strategy calls for the refinery to place a
greater emphasis on the production of petrochemicals, premium
unleaded gasoline and lubricating base oils, Spencer said. The
plant is one of few along the gulf coast with its own packaging
facilities.
   The company plans to complete the cutbacks by the end of the
first quarter 1989, Spencer said.
   The Port Arthur refinery first opened in 1901 and has undergone
numerous renovations, including a $600-million improvement project
in 1980, he said.
</TEXT>
