<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv22-23-1stAdd   10-22 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 22-23-1st Add,0241</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... by Congress.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in December settled Friday at $4.19{ a
bushel, down from $4.28} a week earlier; December corn fell to
$2.83{ a bushel from $2.93}; December oats slipped to $2.50\ a
bushel from $2.52{; and November soybeans tumbled to $7.74} a
bushel from $8.04.
   Livestock futures retreated but pork bellies advanced on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   December live cattle fell to 74.42 cents a pound from 74.75
cents; October feeder cattle dipped to 81.70 cents a pound from 82
cents; December hogs dropped to 41.87 cents a pound from 43.05
cents; and February frozen pork bellies rose to 49.62 cents a pound
from 49 cents.
   Precious metals futures retreated on the Commodity Exchange in
New York.
   December gold fell to $411.50 a troy ounce from $412.50;
December silver dropped to $6.285 a troy ounce from $6.435.
   Energy futures were mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   December West Texas Intermediate crude oil dipped to $14.37 a
barrel from $14.44; November heating oil fell to 42.71 cents a
gallon from 43.21 cents; and November unleaded gasoline rose to
51.22 cents a gallon from 45.42 cents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
