<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Knight-Ridder     10-22 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Knight-Ridder,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder's Profit Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. said Friday its third-quarter
profit fell 4.4 percent from a year ago, due mainly to weak retail
advertising and lower ad revenue.
   For the three-month period ended Sept. 30, Knight-Ridder's
after-tax profit totaled $31.99 million, or 57 cents a share, down
from $33.4 million, or 57 cents a share, in the year-ago period.
The latest quarter's net included $2.19 million from discontinued
operations.
   Earlier this month, the company announced plans to sell its
eight television stations.
   The media company's third quarter revenue rose 5.8 percent to
$503.1 million from $475.6 million.
   ``A lower tax rate and the benefits of the repurchase of our own
stock helped our earnings per share results during the quarter,''
said Robert F. Singleton, senior vice president and chief financial
officer.
   ``Revenue growth from newspaper operations was a disappointing
3.2 percent. Retail and general advertising, mirroring nationwide
trends, were both below our expectations,'' Singleton said.
   For the first nine months, Knight-Ridder's profit totaled
$110.79 million, up 5.4 percent from $105.11 million in the same
period in 1987. Revenue totaled $1.51 billion, up 4.8 percent from
$1.44 billion in the year-earlier period.
</TEXT>
