<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     10-22 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip in Skittish Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices declined in skittish trading as two
OPEC committees continued meetings about the cartel's
overproduction.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, fell 9 cents Friday to close at $14.37 a
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Several other
contract months fell by similar amounts.
   Trading was nervous, although less volatile than in sessions
earlier this week. The November contract for WTI, which expired on
Thursday, dropped 60 cents on Tuesday, soared 79 cents on Wednesday
and then tumbled 80 cents in its final day.
   Oil futures have traveled a rocky road in recent weeks because
of rampant overproduction by members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries and hopes that the OPEC committees
meeting in Madrid might make progress toward limiting the cartel's
output.
   Little concrete news came out of the gathering's first two days.
The pricing and long-term strategy committees ended a second day of
talks Friday with no announcement, and scheduled another round for
Saturday.
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman said Friday progress toward a new
production agreement rested on ironing out sharp differences
between Iraq and Iran.
   OPEC's current ceiling for 12 of its 13 member nations is 15.06
million barrels a day, although current production is estimated at
close to 21 million barrels a day.
   As trading wore on Friday, ``every time a different report of a
news story came out, (the market) would make a big move,'' said Jim
Fiedler, a trader with E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc.
   ``The market's headline-driven,'' he said.
   Refined products traded on the Mercantile Exchange were mixed.
The November contract for home heating oil slipped 0.35 cent to
close at 42.71 cents a gallon.
   But prices for wholesale unleaded gasoline surged higher because
of tight supplies, Fiedler said.
   The November contract for gasoline rose 1.87 cents to settle at
51.22 cents a gallon.
   Fiedler called gasoline trading ``a different world by itself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
